{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "lazy-asset-loader"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
bevy = "0.15"
zip = "2.6"
",
  "main.rs": "//! Lazy Asset Loader for Bevy
//!
//! Demonstrates how to use a custom `AssetSource` + `AssetReader` so that
//! individual assets inside a zip (or any archive / WAD-like format) can be
//! loaded lazily – i.e. only the requested entry is read from the archive,
//! not the whole thing.
//!
//! Usage in Bevy:  `asset_server.load("zip://my_archive.zip/textures/brick.png")`
//!
//! The scheme `zip://` is routed to our custom `ZipAssetReader` which:
//!   1. Splits the path into *archive path* and *entry path*.
//!   2. Opens only that single entry from the zip on the fly.
//!
//! This file is fully self-contained.  Drop a zip file into `assets/` that
//! contains a PNG (e.g. `assets/sample.zip` with `textures/test.png` inside)
//! and load it with:
//!     `asset_server.load::<Image>("zip://sample.zip/textures/test.png")`
//!
//! If you just `cargo run` without any zip the app will start, print a
//! message, and show an empty window – no panic.

use bevy::{
    asset::{
        io::{
            AssetReader, AssetReaderError, AssetSource, AssetSourceId,
            PathStream, Reader,
        },
        AssetApp,
    },
    prelude::*,
};
use std::{
    path::{Path, PathBuf},
    io::Read,
};

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1.  ZipAssetReader – the heart of the lazy loader
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/// An `AssetReader` that treats every path as `<archive>/<entry>` where the
/// first component that ends with `.zip` (case-insensitive) is the archive
/// and everything after it is the entry inside that archive.
///
/// Archives are resolved relative to the normal `assets/` directory.
struct ZipAssetReader {
    /// Root directory for assets (typically `assets/`).
    root: PathBuf,
}

impl ZipAssetReader {
    fn new(root: impl Into<PathBuf>) -> Self {
        Self { root: root.into() }
    }

    /// Given a virtual path like `sample.zip/textures/test.png`, return
    /// `(assets/sample.zip, textures/test.png)`.
    fn split_archive_path<'a>(&self, full: &'a Path) -> Option<(PathBuf, PathBuf)> {
        let mut archive_parts: Vec<&std::ffi::OsStr> = Vec::new();
        let mut found = false;
        let mut entry_start = 0usize;

        for (i, component) in full.components().enumerate() {
            let c = component.as_os_str();
            archive_parts.push(c);
            if c.to_string_lossy().to_lowercase().ends_with(".zip") {
                found = true;
                entry_start = i + 1;
                break;
            }
        }

        if !found {
            return None;
        }

        let archive_rel: PathBuf = archive_parts.iter().collect();
        let archive_abs = self.root.join(archive_rel);

        let entry: PathBuf = full.components().skip(entry_start).collect();

        Some((archive_abs, entry))
    }

    fn read_entry_bytes(&self, path: &Path) -> Result<Vec<u8>, AssetReaderError> {
        let (archive_path, entry_path) = self
            .split_archive_path(path)
            .ok_or_else(|| AssetReaderError::NotFound(path.to_path_buf()))?;

        let file = std::fs::File::open(&archive_path).map_err(|_e| {
            AssetReaderError::NotFound(archive_path.clone())
        })?;

        let mut zip = zip::ZipArchive::new(file).map_err(|_e| {
            AssetReaderError::NotFound(archive_path.clone())
        })?;

        // Zip entries typically use forward slashes.
        let entry_str = entry_path.to_string_lossy().replace('\\', "/");

        let mut entry = zip.by_name(&entry_str).map_err(|_e| {
            AssetReaderError::NotFound(entry_path.clone())
        })?;

        let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(entry.size() as usize);
        entry.read_to_end(&mut buf).map_err(|e| {
            AssetReaderError::Io(
                std::io::Error::new(std::io::ErrorKind::Other, e).into(),
            )
        })?;

        Ok(buf)
    }
}

impl AssetReader for ZipAssetReader {
    fn read<'a>(
        &'a self,
        path: &'a Path,
    ) -> impl std::future::Future<Output = Result<Box<dyn Reader + 'a>, AssetReaderError>> + Send {
        async move {
            let bytes = self.read_entry_bytes(path)?;
            let cursor = std::io::Cursor::new(bytes);
            let reader: Box<dyn Reader> = Box::new(cursor);
            Ok(reader)
        }
    }

    fn read_meta<'a>(
        &'a self,
        path: &'a Path,
    ) -> impl std::future::Future<Output = Result<Box<dyn Reader + 'a>, AssetReaderError>> + Send {
        async move {
            // We don't store .meta files inside the archive.
            Err(AssetReaderError::NotFound(path.to_path_buf()))
        }
    }

    fn read_directory<'a>(
        &'a self,
        path: &'a Path,
    ) -> impl std::future::Future<Output = Result<Box<PathStream>, AssetReaderError>> + Send {
        async move {
            // Directory listing inside a zip is possible but not required for
            // lazy, on-demand loading.  Return "not found" for now.
            Err(AssetReaderError::NotFound(path.to_path_buf()))
        }
    }

    fn is_directory<'a>(
        &'a self,
        path: &'a Path,
    ) -> impl std::future::Future<Output = Result<bool, AssetReaderError>> + Send {
        async move {
            Ok(false)
        }
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 2.  Plugin that registers the custom asset source
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

struct ZipAssetSourcePlugin;

impl Plugin for ZipAssetSourcePlugin {
    fn build(&self, app: &mut App) {
        // Resolve the `assets/` folder the same way Bevy does by default.
        let assets_root = {
            if let Ok(manifest) = std::env::var("CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR") {
                PathBuf::from(manifest).join("assets")
            } else {
                // Fallback: next to the executable.
                let exe = std::env::current_exe().unwrap_or_default();
                exe.parent()
                    .unwrap_or_else(|| Path::new("."))
                    .join("assets")
            }
        };

        let root = assets_root.clone();

        app.register_asset_source(
            AssetSourceId::Name("zip".into()),
            AssetSource::build().with_reader(move || {
                Box::new(ZipAssetReader::new(root.clone()))
            }),
        );

        info!("ZipAssetSourcePlugin registered – assets root: {assets_root:?}");
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// 3.  Tiny demo app
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

#[derive(Resource)]
struct ZipImageHandle(Handle<Image>);

fn setup(
    mut commands: Commands,
    asset_server: Res<AssetServer>,
) {
    commands.spawn(Camera2d);

    // -------------------------------------------------------------------
    // TRY TO LOAD FROM A ZIP
    // Put a file `assets/sample.zip` that contains `textures/test.png`.
    // If the file doesn't exist Bevy will just log a warning – no crash.
    // -------------------------------------------------------------------
    let handle: Handle<Image> =
        asset_server.load("zip://sample.zip/textures/test.png");

    info!("Requested lazy load of zip://sample.zip/textures/test.png");

    commands.insert_resource(ZipImageHandle(handle.clone()));

    // Spawn a sprite so we can see the texture if it loads successfully.
    commands.spawn(Sprite {
        image: handle,
        ..default()
    });
}

fn report_load_state(
    handle: Option<Res<ZipImageHandle>>,
    asset_server: Res<AssetServer>,
    mut reported: Local<bool>,
) {
    if *reported {
        return;
    }
    let Some(handle) = handle else { return };
    if let Some(state) = asset_server.get_load_state(&handle.0) {
        use bevy::asset::LoadState;
        match state {
            LoadState::Loaded => {
                info!("✅ Zip asset loaded successfully!");
                *reported = true;
            }
            LoadState::Failed(ref _e) => {
                warn!("❌ Zip asset failed to load (expected if sample.zip is missing).");
                *reported = true;
            }
            _ => {}
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    App::new()
        .add_plugins(DefaultPlugins)
        .add_plugins(ZipAssetSourcePlugin)
        .add_systems(Startup, setup)
        .add_systems(Update, report_load_state)
        .run();
}
"
}
```

**How it works – key ideas:**

1. **Custom `AssetReader`** (`ZipAssetReader`) instead of a custom `AssetLoader`. This is the critical difference. An `AssetReader` sits at the *I/O layer* and is asked to provide raw bytes for a single path. It only opens the one zip entry that was requested — truly lazy.

2. **Custom asset source scheme (`zip://`)**. The plugin calls `register_asset_source` with the id `"zip"`. When you write `asset_server.load("zip://sample.zip/textures/test.png")`, Bevy routes the request to our `ZipAssetReader`.

3. **Path splitting**. The reader splits the virtual path at the first `.zip` component, giving it the archive path on disk and the entry path inside the archive.

4. **Scalable to WAD3 / custom formats**. You'd replace the `zip` crate calls with your own WAD3 reader that seeks to the right lump — the architecture is identical.

**To test it**: create `assets/sample.zip` containing `textures/test.png` (any PNG). Run `cargo run` and the texture will appear as a sprite.

