Here's a self-contained example that demonstrates how to properly serialize complex nested data with FlatBuffers in Rust, including a multithreaded approach using Rayon. The key insight is that you **cannot** share `FlatBufferBuilder` across threads — instead, you do your parallel work (collecting/preparing data) first, then serialize sequentially into the builder.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "flatbuffer-multithreaded-demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
flatbuffers = "24.3.25"
rayon = "1.10"
",
  "main.rs": "//! Self-contained FlatBuffers serialization demo.
//!
//! Key insight: FlatBufferBuilder is neither Send nor Sync and holds
//! a mutable internal buffer, so you CANNOT share it across threads.
//!
//! The correct pattern is:
//!   1. Do any expensive / parallelisable *preparation* work first
//!      (string cloning, transformations, sorting, filtering, etc.)
//!      using Rayon or Tokio.
//!   2. Feed the prepared data into the FlatBufferBuilder on a
//!      **single thread**, sequentially.
//!
//! Below we define a tiny FlatBuffers schema in code (using the
//! raw FlatBuffers builder API so we don't need `flatc`), and
//! show the full pattern.

use flatbuffers::{FlatBufferBuilder, WIPOffset, ForwardsUOffset};
use rayon::prelude::*;
use std::fmt;

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Domain types (the "complex data" we want to serialize)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct FrontMatter {
    title: String,
    ignored_parsers: Vec<String>,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct Citation {
    author: String,
    year: u32,
    title: String,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct Tag {
    name: String,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct MdxDocument {
    content: String,
    front_matter: Option<FrontMatter>,
    citations: Vec<Citation>,
    tags: Vec<Tag>,
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// FlatBuffer table helpers (normally generated by flatc; we do it by hand
// here so the example is self-contained).
//
// Schema (conceptual):
//
//   table TagBuf           { name: string; }
//   table CitationBuf      { author: string; year: uint; title: string; }
//   table FrontMatterBuf   { title: string; ignored_parsers: [string]; }
//   table MdxDocumentBuf   {
//       content: string;
//       front_matter: FrontMatterBuf;
//       citations: [CitationBuf];
//       tags: [TagBuf];
//   }
//   root_type MdxDocumentBuf;
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/// Build a TagBuf table and return its offset.
fn build_tag<'a>(
    builder: &mut FlatBufferBuilder<'a>,
    tag: &Tag,
) -> WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset> {
    let name = builder.create_string(&tag.name);
    let start = builder.start_table();
    builder.push_slot_always(4, name); // field 0
    builder.end_table(start).as_union_value().into()
}

/// Build a CitationBuf table and return its offset.
fn build_citation<'a>(
    builder: &mut FlatBufferBuilder<'a>,
    citation: &Citation,
) -> WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset> {
    let author = builder.create_string(&citation.author);
    let title = builder.create_string(&citation.title);
    let start = builder.start_table();
    builder.push_slot_always(4, author); // field 0
    builder.push_slot::<u32>(6, citation.year, 0); // field 1
    builder.push_slot_always(8, title);  // field 2
    builder.end_table(start).as_union_value().into()
}

/// Build a FrontMatterBuf table and return its offset.
fn build_front_matter<'a>(
    builder: &mut FlatBufferBuilder<'a>,
    fm: &FrontMatter,
    // Pre-prepared (possibly in parallel) ignored_parsers strings:
    prepared_ignored: &[String],
) -> WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset> {
    // Create strings inside the builder (must be sequential)
    let string_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<&str>> = prepared_ignored
        .iter()
        .map(|s| builder.create_string(s))
        .collect();
    let ignored_vec = builder.create_vector(&string_offsets);
    let title = builder.create_string(&fm.title);

    let start = builder.start_table();
    builder.push_slot_always(4, title);       // field 0
    builder.push_slot_always(6, ignored_vec); // field 1
    builder.end_table(start).as_union_value().into()
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The main serialization routine demonstrating the pattern
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

impl MdxDocument {
    /// Serialize the entire document into a FlatBuffer byte vec.
    ///
    /// Parallel work is done **before** touching the builder.
    fn serialize_to_flatbuffer(&self) -> Vec<u8> {
        // ===================================================================
        // STEP 1 – Parallel preparation (no builder involvement)
        // ===================================================================

        // Example: upper-case all ignored parsers in parallel
        let prepared_ignored: Vec<String> = self
            .front_matter
            .as_ref()
            .map(|fm| {
                fm.ignored_parsers
                    .par_iter()
                    .map(|p| {
                        // Simulate expensive work
                        p.to_uppercase()
                    })
                    .collect()
            })
            .unwrap_or_default();

        // Example: sort citations by year in parallel (just to show rayon)
        let mut sorted_citations = self.citations.clone();
        sorted_citations.par_sort_by_key(|c| c.year);

        // Example: transform tags in parallel
        let prepared_tags: Vec<Tag> = self
            .tags
            .par_iter()
            .map(|t| Tag {
                name: format!("#{}", t.name),
            })
            .collect();

        // ===================================================================
        // STEP 2 – Sequential serialization into the FlatBufferBuilder
        // ===================================================================

        let mut builder = FlatBufferBuilder::with_capacity(1024);

        // -- tags --
        let tag_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset>> = prepared_tags
            .iter()
            .map(|t| build_tag(&mut builder, t))
            .collect();
        let tags_vector = if !tag_offsets.is_empty() {
            // We need to transmute the union offsets to table offsets for create_vector.
            // Since we know they are table offsets this is safe with ForwardsUOffset.
            let table_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Table<'_>>>> =
                tag_offsets.iter().map(|o| WIPOffset::new(o.value())).collect();
            Some(builder.create_vector(&table_offsets))
        } else {
            None
        };

        // -- citations --
        let citation_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset>> = sorted_citations
            .iter()
            .map(|c| build_citation(&mut builder, c))
            .collect();
        let citations_vector = if !citation_offsets.is_empty() {
            let table_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Table<'_>>>> =
                citation_offsets.iter().map(|o| WIPOffset::new(o.value())).collect();
            Some(builder.create_vector(&table_offsets))
        } else {
            None
        };

        // -- front_matter --
        let fm_offset = self.front_matter.as_ref().map(|fm| {
            build_front_matter(&mut builder, fm, &prepared_ignored)
        });

        // -- content --
        let content_offset = builder.create_string(&self.content);

        // -- root table: MdxDocumentBuf --
        let root_start = builder.start_table();
        builder.push_slot_always(4, content_offset); // field 0: content
        if let Some(fm) = fm_offset {
            builder.push_slot_always::<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset>>(6, fm); // field 1
        }
        if let Some(cv) = citations_vector {
            builder.push_slot_always(8, cv); // field 2
        }
        if let Some(tv) = tags_vector {
            builder.push_slot_always(10, tv); // field 3
        }
        let root = builder.end_table(root_start);

        builder.finish(root, None);

        builder.finished_data().to_vec()
    }
}

impl fmt::Display for MdxDocument {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "MdxDocument(content_len={}, citations={}, tags={})",
            self.content.len(), self.citations.len(), self.tags.len())
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Main – build sample data, serialize, report
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

fn main() {
    let doc = MdxDocument {
        content: "# Hello World\n\nThis is some **MDX** content.".into(),
        front_matter: Some(FrontMatter {
            title: "My Document".into(),
            ignored_parsers: vec![
                "remarkGfm".into(),
                "rehypeSlug".into(),
                "remarkMath".into(),
            ],
        }),
        citations: vec![
            Citation { author: "Knuth".into(),   year: 1968, title: "The Art of Computer Programming".into() },
            Citation { author: "Turing".into(),  year: 1936, title: "On Computable Numbers".into() },
            Citation { author: "Dijkstra".into(),year: 1959, title: "A Note on Two Problems".into() },
        ],
        tags: vec![
            Tag { name: "rust".into() },
            Tag { name: "flatbuffers".into() },
            Tag { name: "multithreading".into() },
        ],
    };

    println!("Serializing: {}", doc);
    let bytes = doc.serialize_to_flatbuffer();
    println!("Serialized to {} bytes of FlatBuffer data.", bytes.len());
    println!();
    println!("=== Summary ===");
    println!("The key pattern is:");
    println!("  1. Do parallel work (transforms, sorting, filtering) with Rayon FIRST.");
    println!("  2. Feed the results into FlatBufferBuilder on ONE thread.");
    println!();
    println!("FlatBufferBuilder is !Send + !Sync and requires &mut self,");
    println!("so it fundamentally cannot be shared across threads.");
    println!("This is by design — the buffer is a contiguous byte array");
    println!("that is written back-to-front and cannot support concurrent writes.");
    println!();
    println!("Raw bytes (hex, first 64): ");
    for (i, b) in bytes.iter().take(64).enumerate() {
        print!("{:02x} ", b);
        if (i + 1) % 16 == 0 { println!(); }
    }
    println!();
}
"
}
```

### Key takeaways explained in the code:

1. **`FlatBufferBuilder` cannot be shared across threads** — it's `!Send` and `!Sync` by design because it manages a contiguous byte buffer written back-to-front.

2. **The correct pattern is a two-phase approach:**
   - **Phase 1 (parallel):** Use Rayon's `par_iter` to do all expensive transformations, filtering, sorting, string manipulation, etc. Collect results into plain Rust types (`Vec<String>`, `Vec<Tag>`, etc.).
   - **Phase 2 (sequential):** Feed the prepared data into the `FlatBufferBuilder` on a single thread using `&mut builder`.

3. **The original error** (`cannot borrow builder as mutable, as it is a captured variable in a Fn closure`) happens because `par_iter().map()` requires `Fn` (not `FnMut`), and `builder.create_string()` needs `&mut self`. The solution is simply to not use the builder inside parallel iterators at all.

