Here's a solution that demonstrates how to work around the `enum_dispatch` same-crate limitation by using a procedural-macro-free approach with a custom macro that generates the enum and trait delegation, keeping the three logical layers separate (simulated as modules in a single file for self-contained testing):

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "enum_dispatch_workaround"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
",
  "main.rs": "/// =============================================================================
/// This example demonstrates how to solve the enum_dispatch cross-crate
/// limitation by using a custom declarative macro that generates both the enum
/// and the trait delegation (forwarding) automatically.
///
/// The architecture is split into three logical layers (modules here):
///   - `al`  (Abstract Layer):  traits + the delegation macro
///   - `il`  (Implementation Layer): concrete types implementing the trait
///   - `bl`  (Business Layer): enum definition via the macro + application logic
///
/// The macro `impl_rest_enum!` lives in `al` alongside the trait.  It accepts
/// an enum name and a list of variants and expands to:
///   1. The enum definition
///   2. A `impl Rest for TheEnum` block that delegates every method to the
///      inner variant.
///
/// This gives us the same static-dispatch benefit as `enum_dispatch` without
/// requiring the trait and enum to be in the same crate, and without any
/// procedural macro crate.
/// =============================================================================

// ---- Abstract Layer --------------------------------------------------------
mod al {
    /// The trait with many methods (we show 5 representative ones;
    /// the pattern trivially extends to 20+).
    pub trait Rest {
        fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String;
        fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String;
        fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String;
        fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String;
        fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String;
    }

    /// Declarative macro that generates an enum **and** a delegating `Rest`
    /// impl for it.  Each method simply matches on `self` and forwards the
    /// call to the inner value.
    ///
    /// Usage (in the business layer):
    /// ```ignore
    /// impl_rest_enum! {
    ///     pub enum Item {
    ///         Foo(crate::il::Foo),
    ///         Boo(crate::il::Boo),
    ///     }
    /// }
    /// ```
    #[macro_export]
    macro_rules! impl_rest_enum {
        (
            $(#[$meta:meta])*
            $vis:vis enum $name:ident {
                $( $variant:ident( $ty:ty ) ),* $(,)?
            }
        ) => {
            // 1. Generate the enum itself with tuple variants.
            $(#[$meta])*
            $vis enum $name {
                $( $variant($ty), )*
            }

            // 2. Generate From impls for ergonomic conversion.
            $(
                impl From<$ty> for $name {
                    fn from(v: $ty) -> Self {
                        $name::$variant(v)
                    }
                }
            )*

            // 3. Delegate every `Rest` method.
            impl $crate::al::Rest for $name {
                fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String {
                    match self {
                        $( $name::$variant(inner) => inner.get(url), )*
                    }
                }

                fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
                    match self {
                        $( $name::$variant(inner) => inner.post(url, body), )*
                    }
                }

                fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
                    match self {
                        $( $name::$variant(inner) => inner.put(url, body), )*
                    }
                }

                fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String {
                    match self {
                        $( $name::$variant(inner) => inner.delete(url), )*
                    }
                }

                fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
                    match self {
                        $( $name::$variant(inner) => inner.patch(url, body), )*
                    }
                }
            }
        };
    }
}

// ---- Implementation Layer --------------------------------------------------
mod il {
    use crate::al::Rest;

    #[derive(Debug, Clone)]
    pub struct Foo {
        pub base_url: String,
    }

    impl Rest for Foo {
        fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo::get  {} {}", self.base_url, url)
        }
        fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo::post {} {} body={}", self.base_url, url, body)
        }
        fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo::put  {} {} body={}", self.base_url, url, body)
        }
        fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo::delete {} {}", self.base_url, url)
        }
        fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo::patch {} {} body={}", self.base_url, url, body)
        }
    }

    #[derive(Debug, Clone)]
    pub struct Boo {
        pub token: String,
    }

    impl Rest for Boo {
        fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo::get  [token={}] {}", self.token, url)
        }
        fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo::post [token={}] {} body={}", self.token, url, body)
        }
        fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo::put  [token={}] {} body={}", self.token, url, body)
        }
        fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo::delete [token={}] {}", self.token, url)
        }
        fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo::patch [token={}] {} body={}", self.token, url, body)
        }
    }
}

// ---- Business Layer --------------------------------------------------------
mod bl {
    use crate::al::Rest;

    // Use the macro from `al` to create the enum + delegation in *this* layer.
    // No circular dependency: `al` knows nothing about `il` or `bl`.
    impl_rest_enum! {
        #[derive(Debug, Clone)]
        pub enum Item {
            Foo(crate::il::Foo),
            Boo(crate::il::Boo),
        }
    }

    /// A function that works with any `Rest` implementor – including `Item`.
    pub fn exercise(item: &Item) {
        println!("{}", item.get("/users"));
        println!("{}", item.post("/users", r#"{"name":"Alice"}"#));
        println!("{}", item.put("/users/1", r#"{"name":"Bob"}"#));
        println!("{}", item.delete("/users/2"));
        println!("{}", item.patch("/users/3", r#"{"email":"c@d.com"}"#));
    }

    /// Demonstrate that generic code accepting `impl Rest` works too.
    pub fn generic_consumer(r: &impl Rest) {
        println!("generic: {}", r.get("/health"));
    }
}

// ---- Main ------------------------------------------------------------------
fn main() {
    use crate::bl::Item;
    use crate::il::{Boo, Foo};

    let foo = Foo {
        base_url: "https://api.foo.io".into(),
    };
    let boo = Boo {
        token: "s3cret".into(),
    };

    // Convert concrete types into the enum via the generated `From` impls.
    let item_foo: Item = foo.clone().into();
    let item_boo: Item = boo.clone().into();

    println!("=== Exercising Foo variant ===");
    bl::exercise(&item_foo);

    println!();
    println!("=== Exercising Boo variant ===");
    bl::exercise(&item_boo);

    println!();
    println!("=== Generic consumer with Item (static dispatch) ===");
    bl::generic_consumer(&item_foo);
    bl::generic_consumer(&item_boo);

    println!();
    println!("=== Collect heterogeneous items in a Vec<Item> ===");
    let items: Vec<Item> = vec![foo.into(), boo.into()];
    for (i, item) in items.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("item[{}]: {}", i, crate::al::Rest::get(item, "/ping"));
    }

    println!();
    println!("All done – no dynamic dispatch (dyn), no enum_dispatch crate, no circular deps!");
}
"
}
```

### How it works

The key insight is replacing the `enum_dispatch` proc-macro with a **declarative macro** (`impl_rest_enum!`) that lives in the abstract layer (`al`) alongside the trait. This macro:

1. **Generates the enum** with tuple variants wrapping each concrete type.
2. **Generates `From` impls** for ergonomic conversion.
3. **Generates a `Rest` impl for the enum** that `match`es on each variant and delegates to the inner value.

**Why this solves the problem:**

- **`al`** only defines the trait and the macro — it knows nothing about `il` or `bl`.
- **`il`** depends on `al` for the trait — no cycle.
- **`bl`** depends on both `al` (trait + macro) and `il` (concrete types) — invokes the macro to wire everything together. No cycle.

The delegation is fully static (no `dyn`, no vtable), just like `enum_dispatch`. For 20 methods you simply list them all inside the macro's `impl` block once — the `$( $name::$variant(inner) => ... )*` repetition handles any number of variants automatically.

