Here's a self-contained demonstration showing how to use a trait-based approach to avoid duplicating `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` downcasting for every inner type. The key idea is to register a list of "type erasure" handlers via a trait (`Inspectable`) and a macro, so you only list each inner type once.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "downcast_any_vec_option"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
",
  "main.rs": "use std::any::Any;

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Minimal stubs so the example compiles without egui.
// In your real code, replace these with actual egui types and widgets.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
struct Ui;
impl Ui {
    fn label(&self, text: &str) { println!("  [label] {}", text); }
}

fn string_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, v: &mut String, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("{}: String = \"{}\"", title, v));
}
fn i_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, v: &mut i32, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("{}: i32 = {}", title, v));
}
fn f_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, v: &mut f32, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("{}: f32 = {}", title, v));
}
fn bool_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, v: &mut bool, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("{}: bool = {}", title, v));
}
fn usize_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, v: &mut usize, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("{}: usize = {}", title, v));
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The trait that every "inspectable" inner type implements.
// It knows how to render a single value, and we also use it to create
// defaults for Option/Vec add operations.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
trait Inspectable: Any + Default {
    fn inspect(&mut self, ui: &Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool);
}

impl Inspectable for String {
    fn inspect(&mut self, ui: &Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        string_property(ui, title, self, interactable);
    }
}
impl Inspectable for i32 {
    fn inspect(&mut self, ui: &Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        i_property(ui, title, self, interactable);
    }
}
impl Inspectable for f32 {
    fn inspect(&mut self, ui: &Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        f_property(ui, title, self, interactable);
    }
}
impl Inspectable for bool {
    fn inspect(&mut self, ui: &Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        bool_property(ui, title, self, interactable);
    }
}
impl Inspectable for usize {
    fn inspect(&mut self, ui: &Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        usize_property(ui, title, self, interactable);
    }
}

// Example custom type
#[derive(Default, Debug)]
struct MyEnum {
    variant: String,
}
impl Inspectable for MyEnum {
    fn inspect(&mut self, ui: &Ui, title: &str, _interactable: bool) {
        ui.label(&format!("{}: MyEnum({:?})", title, self.variant));
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Generic list_property / option_property that work for any T: Inspectable
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn list_property<T: Inspectable>(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value_mut: &mut Vec<T>, interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("▼ {} (Vec, len={})", title, value_mut.len()));
    // In real code: collapsing header, add/remove buttons, etc.
    for (i, item) in value_mut.iter_mut().enumerate() {
        item.inspect(ui, &format!("  [{}]", i), interactable);
    }
}

fn option_property<T: Inspectable>(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value_mut: &mut Option<T>, interactable: bool) {
    match value_mut {
        Some(inner) => {
            ui.label(&format!("Option {} = Some:", title));
            inner.inspect(ui, &format!("  {}", title), interactable);
        }
        None => {
            ui.label(&format!("Option {} = None", title));
        }
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Type-erased handler: a function pointer that tries to downcast & render.
// Returns true if it handled the value.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
type Handler = fn(&Ui, &str, &mut dyn Any, bool) -> bool;

/// Build a handler for a single concrete type T.
fn make_scalar_handler<T: Inspectable>() -> Handler {
    |ui, title, value, interactable| {
        if let Some(v) = value.downcast_mut::<T>() {
            v.inspect(ui, title, interactable);
            true
        } else {
            false
        }
    }
}

/// Build a handler for Vec<T>.
fn make_vec_handler<T: Inspectable>() -> Handler {
    |ui, title, value, interactable| {
        if let Some(v) = value.downcast_mut::<Vec<T>>() {
            list_property(ui, title, v, interactable);
            true
        } else {
            false
        }
    }
}

/// Build a handler for Option<T>.
fn make_option_handler<T: Inspectable>() -> Handler {
    |ui, title, value, interactable| {
        if let Some(v) = value.downcast_mut::<Option<T>>() {
            option_property(ui, title, v, interactable);
            true
        } else {
            false
        }
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Macro: register a type once, get scalar + Vec + Option handlers for free.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
macro_rules! register_inspectable_types {
    ($($t:ty),* $(,)?) => {
        fn build_handlers() -> Vec<Handler> {
            let mut handlers: Vec<Handler> = Vec::new();
            $(
                handlers.push(make_scalar_handler::<$t>());
                handlers.push(make_vec_handler::<$t>());
                handlers.push(make_option_handler::<$t>());
            )*
            handlers
        }
    };
}

// Register all your types HERE — just once!
register_inspectable_types!(
    String,
    i32,
    f32,
    bool,
    usize,
    MyEnum,
);

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The unified downcast_property — no more duplication!
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn downcast_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value_mut: &mut dyn Any, interactable: bool) {
    let handlers = build_handlers();
    for handler in &handlers {
        if handler(ui, title, value_mut, interactable) {
            return;
        }
    }
    ui.label(&format!("Field {}: unknown type", title));
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Demo
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn main() {
    let ui = Ui;

    println!("=== Scalar types ===");
    downcast_property(&ui, "name", &mut String::from("hello"), true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "count", &mut 42_i32, true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "ratio", &mut 3.14_f32, true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "flag", &mut true, true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "idx", &mut 7_usize, true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "kind", &mut MyEnum { variant: "A".into() }, true);

    println!();
    println!("=== Vec types (auto-handled) ===");
    downcast_property(&ui, "names", &mut vec!["a".to_string(), "b".to_string()], true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "numbers", &mut vec![1_i32, 2, 3], true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "floats", &mut vec![1.0_f32, 2.5], true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "enums", &mut vec![MyEnum { variant: "X".into() }], true);

    println!();
    println!("=== Option types (auto-handled) ===");
    downcast_property(&ui, "opt_str", &mut Some(String::from("world")), true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "opt_none", &mut None::<i32>, true);
    downcast_property(&ui, "opt_enum", &mut Some(MyEnum { variant: "Z".into() }), true);

    println!();
    println!("=== Unknown type ===");
    downcast_property(&ui, "mystery", &mut 42_u64, true);
}
"
}
```

### How it works

1. **`Inspectable` trait** — Every type that can appear in your properties panel implements this trait, providing an `inspect` method that knows how to render that specific type.

2. **Generic `list_property` / `option_property`** — These are written once, generic over `T: Inspectable`. No duplication per inner type.

3. **Type-erased handlers** — Functions `make_scalar_handler<T>()`, `make_vec_handler<T>()`, and `make_option_handler<T>()` each return a `fn` pointer that tries to downcast `&mut dyn Any` to `T`, `Vec<T>`, or `Option<T>` respectively.

4. **`register_inspectable_types!` macro** — You list each type **once**. The macro automatically generates scalar, `Vec`, and `Option` handlers for every listed type. Adding a new type means adding one line to the macro invocation and one `impl Inspectable` block.

5. **`downcast_property`** — Simply iterates through the generated handlers until one matches. No more manual enumeration of `Vec<String>`, `Vec<i32>`, `Option<String>`, etc.

