Here's a self-contained example that demonstrates how to properly serialize complex nested data with FlatBuffers in Rust, both single-threaded and multi-threaded. The key insight is that you **cannot** share `FlatBufferBuilder` across threads — instead, you collect/prepare your data in parallel first, then serialize sequentially into the builder.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "flatbuffer-demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
flatbuffers = "24.3.25"
rayon = "1.10"
",
  "main.rs": "use flatbuffers::{FlatBufferBuilder, WIPOffset};
use rayon::prelude::*;

// ============================================================
// Since we don't have a .fbs schema file and flatc-generated code,
// we'll build the flatbuffer tables manually using the raw API.
// This mirrors what generated code would do.
//
// Schema (conceptual):
//
// table FrontMatter {
//   ignored_parsers: [string];
//   title: string;
// }
//
// table Tag {
//   name: string;
//   value: string;
// }
//
// table Citation {
//   key: string;
//   reference: string;
// }
//
// table MdxParsingResult {
//   parsed_content: string;
//   front_matter: FrontMatter;
//   tags: [Tag];
//   citations: [Citation];
// }
// ============================================================

/// Simulated domain structs
#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
struct FrontMatter {
    ignored_parsers: Vec<String>,
    title: String,
}

#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
struct Tag {
    name: String,
    value: String,
}

#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
struct Citation {
    key: String,
    reference: String,
}

#[derive(Clone, Debug)]
struct MdxParsingResult {
    content: String,
    front_matter: Option<FrontMatter>,
    tags: Vec<Tag>,
    citations: Vec<Citation>,
}

// ============================================================
// KEY LESSON:
//
// FlatBufferBuilder is NOT Send, NOT Sync, and requires &mut self
// for every operation. You CANNOT share it across threads.
//
// The correct pattern is:
//   1. Do any expensive computation / string processing in parallel
//      BEFORE touching the builder.
//   2. Feed the pre-computed results into the builder on a single thread.
//
// If you have very large nested structures, you can also use
// separate FlatBufferBuilders per sub-tree in parallel, then
// copy the bytes into a final buffer — but that's rarely needed.
// ============================================================

impl MdxParsingResult {
    /// Serialize the entire struct into a flatbuffer byte vec.
    ///
    /// Heavy prep work (string transformations, etc.) is done in
    /// parallel with rayon. The actual builder calls are sequential.
    fn serialize_to_flatbuffer(&self) -> Vec<u8> {
        // ----------------------------------------------------------
        // PHASE 1 (parallel): expensive prep work
        // ----------------------------------------------------------

        // Example: maybe we need to do some heavy processing on each
        // ignored_parser string. We do that in parallel and collect
        // the results into a Vec<String>.
        let prepared_ignored_parsers: Option<Vec<String>> =
            self.front_matter.as_ref().map(|fm| {
                fm.ignored_parsers
                    .par_iter()
                    .map(|s| {
                        // Simulate expensive work
                        let processed = s.to_uppercase(); // placeholder
                        processed
                    })
                    .collect()
            });

        // Similarly, prepare tags and citations in parallel
        let prepared_tags: Vec<(String, String)> = self
            .tags
            .par_iter()
            .map(|t| {
                // Simulate expensive work per tag
                (t.name.trim().to_string(), t.value.trim().to_string())
            })
            .collect();

        let prepared_citations: Vec<(String, String)> = self
            .citations
            .par_iter()
            .map(|c| {
                (c.key.trim().to_string(), c.reference.trim().to_string())
            })
            .collect();

        // ----------------------------------------------------------
        // PHASE 2 (single-threaded): feed into FlatBufferBuilder
        // ----------------------------------------------------------
        let mut builder = FlatBufferBuilder::with_capacity(1024);

        // --- Serialize FrontMatter ---
        let fm_offset = if let (Some(fm), Some(prepared)) =
            (self.front_matter.as_ref(), &prepared_ignored_parsers)
        {
            // Create each string, collect offsets
            let parser_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<&str>> = prepared
                .iter()
                .map(|s| builder.create_string(s))
                .collect();
            let parsers_vec = builder.create_vector(&parser_offsets);

            let title_offset = builder.create_string(&fm.title);

            // Build FrontMatter table manually
            let mut fm_builder = flatbuffers::TableBuilder::new(&mut builder);
            // field 0: ignored_parsers (vector of strings)
            fm_builder.push_slot_always(4, parsers_vec); // voffset 4
            // field 1: title (string)
            fm_builder.push_slot_always(6, title_offset); // voffset 6
            Some(fm_builder.finish())
        } else {
            None
        };

        // --- Serialize Tags ---
        let tag_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset>> = prepared_tags
            .iter()
            .map(|(name, value)| {
                let name_off = builder.create_string(name);
                let value_off = builder.create_string(value);
                let mut tag_builder = flatbuffers::TableBuilder::new(&mut builder);
                tag_builder.push_slot_always(4, name_off);
                tag_builder.push_slot_always(6, value_off);
                tag_builder.finish()
            })
            .collect();
        let tags_vec = builder.create_vector(&tag_offsets);

        // --- Serialize Citations ---
        let citation_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset>> = prepared_citations
            .iter()
            .map(|(key, reference)| {
                let key_off = builder.create_string(key);
                let ref_off = builder.create_string(reference);
                let mut cit_builder = flatbuffers::TableBuilder::new(&mut builder);
                cit_builder.push_slot_always(4, key_off);
                cit_builder.push_slot_always(6, ref_off);
                cit_builder.finish()
            })
            .collect();
        let citations_vec = builder.create_vector(&citation_offsets);

        // --- Serialize root MdxParsingResult ---
        let content_offset = builder.create_string(&self.content);

        let mut root_builder = flatbuffers::TableBuilder::new(&mut builder);
        // field 0: parsed_content
        root_builder.push_slot_always(4, content_offset);
        // field 1: front_matter (optional)
        if let Some(fm_off) = fm_offset {
            root_builder.push_slot_always(6, fm_off);
        }
        // field 2: tags
        root_builder.push_slot_always(8, tags_vec);
        // field 3: citations
        root_builder.push_slot_always(10, citations_vec);

        let root = root_builder.finish();
        builder.finish_minimal(root);

        builder.finished_data().to_vec()
    }
}

// ============================================================
// Demonstrate reading the buffer back (manual, no generated code)
// ============================================================

fn read_back_demo(buf: &[u8]) {
    let root = flatbuffers::root::<flatbuffers::Table>(buf)
        .expect("Failed to read root table");

    // field 0 (voffset 4): parsed_content string
    if let Some(content) = root.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&str>>(4, None) {
        println!("  parsed_content: {}", content);
    }

    // field 1 (voffset 6): front_matter table
    if let Some(fm) = root.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Table>>(6, None) {
        println!("  front_matter:");
        if let Some(title) = fm.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&str>>(6, None) {
            println!("    title: {}", title);
        }
        if let Some(parsers) = fm.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Vector<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&str>>>>(4, None) {
            print!("    ignored_parsers: [");
            for i in 0..parsers.len() {
                if i > 0 { print!(", "); }
                print!("{}", parsers.get(i));
            }
            println!("]");
        }
    }

    // field 2 (voffset 8): tags
    if let Some(tags) = root.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Vector<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Table>>>>(8, None) {
        println!("  tags ({}):", tags.len());
        for i in 0..tags.len() {
            let tag = tags.get(i);
            let name = tag.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&str>>(4, None).unwrap_or("");
            let value = tag.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&str>>(6, None).unwrap_or("");
            println!("    [{}] {} = {}", i, name, value);
        }
    }

    // field 3 (voffset 10): citations
    if let Some(cits) = root.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Vector<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<flatbuffers::Table>>>>(10, None) {
        println!("  citations ({}):", cits.len());
        for i in 0..cits.len() {
            let cit = cits.get(i);
            let key = cit.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&str>>(4, None).unwrap_or("");
            let reference = cit.get::<flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&str>>(6, None).unwrap_or("");
            println!("    [{}] {} -> {}", i, key, reference);
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    println!("=== FlatBuffer Serialization Demo ===");
    println!();
    println!("KEY INSIGHT: FlatBufferBuilder cannot be shared across threads.");
    println!("Do expensive work in parallel FIRST, then serialize single-threaded.");
    println!();

    let data = MdxParsingResult {
        content: "# Hello World\nThis is some MDX content.".to_string(),
        front_matter: Some(FrontMatter {
            ignored_parsers: vec![
                "markdown-it".to_string(),
                "remark".to_string(),
                "rehype".to_string(),
                "unified".to_string(),
            ],
            title: "My Document".to_string(),
        }),
        tags: vec![
            Tag { name: "language".into(), value: "rust".into() },
            Tag { name: "category".into(), value: "serialization".into() },
            Tag { name: "difficulty".into(), value: "medium".into() },
        ],
        citations: vec![
            Citation {
                key: "flatbuffers2024".into(),
                reference: "Google FlatBuffers documentation, 2024".into(),
            },
            Citation {
                key: "rust2024".into(),
                reference: "The Rust Programming Language, 2024 Edition".into(),
            },
        ],
    };

    let bytes = data.serialize_to_flatbuffer();
    println!("Serialized {} bytes", bytes.len());
    println!();

    println!("--- Reading back ---");
    read_back_demo(&bytes);
    println!();

    // --- Demonstrate parallel serialization of MULTIPLE items ---
    println!("--- Parallel serialization of multiple items ---");
    let items: Vec<MdxParsingResult> = (0..8)
        .map(|i| MdxParsingResult {
            content: format!("Content for document {}", i),
            front_matter: Some(FrontMatter {
                ignored_parsers: vec![format!("parser-a-{}", i), format!("parser-b-{}", i)],
                title: format!("Document {}", i),
            }),
            tags: vec![Tag {
                name: "index".into(),
                value: i.to_string(),
            }],
            citations: vec![],
        })
        .collect();

    // Each item gets its OWN builder — this is perfectly parallel!
    let all_buffers: Vec<Vec<u8>> = items
        .par_iter()
        .map(|item| item.serialize_to_flatbuffer())
        .collect();

    for (i, buf) in all_buffers.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("Item {} -> {} bytes", i, buf.len());
    }

    println!();
    println!("Done! All serialization completed successfully.");
}
"
}
```

## Key Takeaways

The fundamental issue is that `FlatBufferBuilder` requires `&mut self` for every operation and is neither `Send` nor `Sync`. **You cannot share it across threads.** The solution follows a two-phase pattern:

1. **Phase 1 (Parallel):** Use `rayon`'s `par_iter()` to do all expensive computation (string processing, data transformation, etc.) and collect results into plain `Vec`s.

2. **Phase 2 (Sequential):** Feed the pre-computed results into a single `FlatBufferBuilder` on one thread.

For serializing **multiple independent items**, give each item its own `FlatBufferBuilder` — then the items themselves can be processed in parallel trivially with `par_iter().map(|item| item.serialize_to_flatbuffer()).collect()`.

