Here's a self-contained demonstration that shows how to avoid duplicating `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` downcasting code in Rust by using a trait-based registry approach. Since `egui` UI code requires a full GUI setup, I've replaced the UI parts with simple console output to demonstrate the pattern clearly.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "downcast_demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
",
  "main.rs": "use std::any::Any;

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The key idea: define a trait that erases the inner type of Vec<T> / Option<T>,
// then implement it for all T you care about via a macro. Register "type-erasure
// probe" functions in a static slice so that `downcast_property` can iterate
// over them instead of hand-writing every concrete instantiation.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/// Trait for values that know how to render themselves as a "property".
/// In real code this would call egui; here we just print to stdout.
trait PropertyRenderable: Any {
    fn render_property(&mut self, title: &str, interactable: bool);
    fn default_boxed() -> Box<dyn PropertyRenderable>
    where
        Self: Sized;
}

// -- Implement for leaf types ------------------------------------------------

impl PropertyRenderable for String {
    fn render_property(&mut self, title: &str, _interactable: bool) {
        println!("  [String]  {}: {:?}", title, self);
    }
    fn default_boxed() -> Box<dyn PropertyRenderable> {
        Box::new(String::default())
    }
}

impl PropertyRenderable for i32 {
    fn render_property(&mut self, title: &str, _interactable: bool) {
        println!("  [i32]     {}: {}", title, self);
    }
    fn default_boxed() -> Box<dyn PropertyRenderable> {
        Box::new(i32::default())
    }
}

impl PropertyRenderable for f32 {
    fn render_property(&mut self, title: &str, _interactable: bool) {
        println!("  [f32]     {}: {}", title, self);
    }
    fn default_boxed() -> Box<dyn PropertyRenderable> {
        Box::new(f32::default())
    }
}

impl PropertyRenderable for bool {
    fn render_property(&mut self, title: &str, _interactable: bool) {
        println!("  [bool]    {}: {}", title, self);
    }
    fn default_boxed() -> Box<dyn PropertyRenderable> {
        Box::new(bool::default())
    }
}

impl PropertyRenderable for usize {
    fn render_property(&mut self, title: &str, _interactable: bool) {
        println!("  [usize]   {}: {}", title, self);
    }
    fn default_boxed() -> Box<dyn PropertyRenderable> {
        Box::new(usize::default())
    }
}

// An example custom type
#[derive(Debug, Default, Clone)]
struct DataType {
    pub name: String,
    pub code: i32,
}

impl PropertyRenderable for DataType {
    fn render_property(&mut self, title: &str, _interactable: bool) {
        println!("  [DataType] {}: {:?}", title, self);
    }
    fn default_boxed() -> Box<dyn PropertyRenderable> {
        Box::new(DataType::default())
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Generic list / option rendering (mirrors your list_property / option_property)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

fn list_property<T: PropertyRenderable + Default + 'static>(
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut Vec<T>,
    interactable: bool,
) {
    println!("  [Vec<{}>] {} (len={}):", std::any::type_name::<T>(), title, value_mut.len());
    for (i, item) in value_mut.iter_mut().enumerate() {
        let sub_title = format!("{}[{}]", title, i);
        item.render_property(&sub_title, interactable);
    }
}

fn option_property<T: PropertyRenderable + Default + 'static>(
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut Option<T>,
    interactable: bool,
) {
    match value_mut {
        Some(inner) => {
            println!("  [Option<{}>] {} = Some:", std::any::type_name::<T>(), title);
            inner.render_property(title, interactable);
        }
        None => {
            println!("  [Option<{}>] {} = None", std::any::type_name::<T>(), title);
        }
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// "Probe" function type: tries to downcast `&mut dyn Any` to a specific
// `Vec<T>` or `Option<T>` and, if successful, renders it. Returns true
// if the downcast succeeded.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

type ProbeFn = fn(&mut dyn Any, &str, bool) -> bool;

/// Macro that, for every listed type T, generates two probe functions
/// (one for Vec<T>, one for Option<T>) and collects them in a slice.
macro_rules! register_property_types {
    ( $( $t:ty ),* $(,)? ) => {
        fn get_probes() -> &'static [ProbeFn] {
            static PROBES: &[ProbeFn] = &[
                $(
                    // Vec<T> probe
                    |val: &mut dyn Any, title: &str, interactable: bool| -> bool {
                        if let Some(v) = val.downcast_mut::<Vec<$t>>() {
                            list_property(title, v, interactable);
                            true
                        } else {
                            false
                        }
                    },
                    // Option<T> probe
                    |val: &mut dyn Any, title: &str, interactable: bool| -> bool {
                        if let Some(o) = val.downcast_mut::<Option<$t>>() {
                            option_property(title, o, interactable);
                            true
                        } else {
                            false
                        }
                    },
                )*
            ];
            PROBES
        }
    };
}

// Register all the inner types you want to support inside Vec<> / Option<>.
// Add new types here — no need to touch downcast_property!
register_property_types!(
    String,
    i32,
    f32,
    bool,
    usize,
    DataType,
);

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The main dispatcher — now Vec/Option cases are handled by the probe table.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub fn downcast_property(
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut (dyn Any + 'static),
    interactable: bool,
) {
    // 1. Try leaf / scalar types first
    if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<String>() {
        v.render_property(title, interactable);
        return;
    }
    if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<i32>() {
        v.render_property(title, interactable);
        return;
    }
    if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<f32>() {
        v.render_property(title, interactable);
        return;
    }
    if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<bool>() {
        v.render_property(title, interactable);
        return;
    }
    if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<usize>() {
        v.render_property(title, interactable);
        return;
    }
    if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<DataType>() {
        v.render_property(title, interactable);
        return;
    }

    // 2. Automatically try every registered Vec<T> and Option<T>
    for probe in get_probes() {
        if probe(value_mut, title, interactable) {
            return;
        }
    }

    // 3. Unknown
    println!("  [UNKNOWN] Field '{}': unknown type", title);
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Demo
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

fn main() {
    println!("=== Scalar types ===");
    downcast_property("my_string", &mut String::from("hello"), true);
    downcast_property("my_int", &mut 42i32, true);
    downcast_property("my_float", &mut 3.14f32, true);
    downcast_property("my_bool", &mut true, true);

    println!();
    println!("=== Vec types (auto-dispatched) ===");
    downcast_property(
        "string_list",
        &mut vec!["alpha".to_string(), "beta".to_string()],
        true,
    );
    downcast_property("int_list", &mut vec![1i32, 2, 3], true);
    downcast_property(
        "data_list",
        &mut vec![
            DataType { name: "A".into(), code: 1 },
            DataType { name: "B".into(), code: 2 },
        ],
        true,
    );

    println!();
    println!("=== Option types (auto-dispatched) ===");
    downcast_property("opt_string_some", &mut Some("world".to_string()), true);
    let none_string: &mut Option<String> = &mut None;
    downcast_property("opt_string_none", none_string, true);
    downcast_property("opt_i32", &mut Some(99i32), true);
    downcast_property(
        "opt_data",
        &mut Some(DataType { name: "X".into(), code: 7 }),
        true,
    );

    println!();
    println!("=== Unknown type ===");
    downcast_property("mystery", &mut 123u64, true);

    println!();
    println!("Done! To add support for a new type inside Vec<>/Option<>,");
    println!("just add it to the register_property_types!() macro call.");
}
"
}
```

**How it works:**

1. **`PropertyRenderable` trait** — Each leaf type (`String`, `i32`, `f32`, `bool`, `DataType`, etc.) implements this trait so it knows how to render itself. In your real code, this would call egui widget functions.

2. **`register_property_types!()` macro** — This is the key. You list every inner type *once*, and the macro generates probe functions for both `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` for each type. The probes are collected into a static slice.

3. **`downcast_property()`** — After checking scalar/leaf types, it iterates through the probe table. Each probe tries to downcast to `Vec<T>` or `Option<T>` for a specific `T`. If it matches, it calls `list_property` or `option_property` and returns.

4. **Adding a new type** — Just implement `PropertyRenderable` for it and add it to the `register_property_types!(...)` call. No more duplicating `Vec<NewType>` / `Option<NewType>` branches!

