Here's a solution that uses a custom `Helper` with a `Hinter` to display a continuation prompt on subsequent lines, combined with `Cmd::Newline` for inserting newlines via Ctrl+J:

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "rustyline-continuation"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
rustyline = "14.0.0"
",
  "main.rs": "use rustyline::{
    Cmd, DefaultEditor, Editor, Event::KeySeq, EventHandler::Simple, KeyEvent, Modifiers,
    Result,
    highlight::Highlighter,
    hint::{Hint, Hinter},
    history::DefaultHistory,
    validate::{ValidationContext, ValidationResult, Validator},
    completion::Completer,
    Helper,
};
use std::borrow::Cow;

#[derive(Helper, Completer)]
struct MultilineHelper {
    continuation_prompt: String,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct ContinuationHint {
    text: String,
}

impl Hint for ContinuationHint {
    fn display(&self) -> &str {
        &self.text
    }

    fn completion(&self) -> Option<&str> {
        None
    }
}

impl Hinter for MultilineHelper {
    type Hint = ContinuationHint;

    fn hint(&self, _line: &str, _pos: usize, _ctx: &rustyline::Context<'_>) -> Option<Self::Hint> {
        // We don't use hints for the continuation prompt in this approach
        None
    }
}

impl Highlighter for MultilineHelper {
    fn highlight_prompt<'b, 's: 'b, 'p: 'b>(
        &'s self,
        prompt: &'p str,
        default: bool,
    ) -> Cow<'b, str> {
        Cow::Borrowed(prompt)
    }

    fn highlight<'l>(&self, line: &'l str, _pos: usize) -> Cow<'l, str> {
        // Insert the continuation prompt after each newline in the buffer
        if line.contains('\n') {
            let replaced = line.replace('\n', &format!("\n{}", self.continuation_prompt));
            Cow::Owned(replaced)
        } else {
            Cow::Borrowed(line)
        }
    }

    fn highlight_char(&self, _line: &str, _pos: usize, _forced: bool) -> bool {
        true
    }
}

impl Validator for MultilineHelper {
    fn validate(&self, _ctx: &mut ValidationContext) -> Result<ValidationResult> {
        Ok(ValidationResult::Valid(None))
    }
}

fn main() {
    let helper = MultilineHelper {
        continuation_prompt: ".. ".to_string(),
    };

    let mut rl: Editor<MultilineHelper, DefaultHistory> = Editor::new().unwrap();
    rl.set_helper(Some(helper));

    // Bind Ctrl+J to insert a newline (Cmd::Newline)
    rl.bind_sequence(
        KeySeq(vec![KeyEvent::new('j', Modifiers::CTRL)]),
        Simple(Cmd::Newline),
    );

    println!("Simple REPL with multiline support.");
    println!("Press Ctrl+J to insert a newline, Enter to submit, Ctrl+C/Ctrl+D to exit.");
    println!();

    loop {
        let readline = rl.readline(">> ");

        match readline {
            Ok(line) => {
                if !line.is_empty() {
                    let _ = rl.add_history_entry(line.as_str());
                }
                println!("You entered:");
                println!("{}", line);
                println!("---");
            }
            Err(rustyline::error::ReadlineError::Interrupted) => {
                println!("Ctrl-C");
                break;
            }
            Err(rustyline::error::ReadlineError::Eof) => {
                println!("Ctrl-D");
                break;
            }
            Err(err) => {
                println!("Error: {:?}", err);
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}
"
}
```

**How it works:**

1. **`Cmd::Newline`** is bound to Ctrl+J, which inserts a literal newline character into the input buffer.

2. **The `Highlighter` trait** is implemented on a custom helper. The `highlight` method replaces each `
` in the buffer with `
..` (the continuation prompt). This makes the continuation prompt appear as part of the rendered output but it's **not part of the actual editable text** — it's purely a display artifact from the highlighter.

3. **`highlight_char`** returns `true` to ensure the highlighter is always active and re-renders on every keystroke.

The continuation prompt (`.. `) is read-only because it exists only in the highlighted display, not in the actual line buffer. When you press Enter to submit, the returned string contains only the real content with newlines — no continuation prompt text.

