Looking at this problem, I need to work with the `pavao` crate (which provides SMB functionality in Rust) to recursively list directories. The `pavao` crate is the most common Rust SMB client library.

Let me provide a working solution using the `pavao` crate, which provides synchronous SMB operations including directory listing:

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "smb-recursive-list"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
pavao = "0.2"
",
  "main.rs": "use pavao::{SmbClient, SmbCredentials, SmbDirentType, SmbOptions};
use std::error::Error;

fn list_dir_recursive(
    client: &SmbClient,
    base_share: &str,
    path: &str,
    depth: usize,
) -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error>> {
    let full_path = if path.is_empty() {
        base_share.to_string()
    } else {
        format!("{}/{}", base_share, path)
    };

    let entries = client.list_dir(&full_path)?;

    for entry in entries {
        let name = entry.name();

        // Skip . and ..
        if name == "." || name == ".." {
            continue;
        }

        let relative_path = if path.is_empty() {
            name.to_string()
        } else {
            format!("{}/{}", path, name)
        };

        let indent = "  ".repeat(depth);

        match entry.get_type() {
            SmbDirentType::Dir => {
                println!("{}[DIR]  {}", indent, relative_path);
                // Recurse into subdirectory
                if let Err(e) = list_dir_recursive(client, base_share, &relative_path, depth + 1) {
                    eprintln!("{}  Error entering {}: {}", indent, relative_path, e);
                }
            }
            SmbDirentType::File => {
                println!("{}[FILE] {}", indent, relative_path);
            }
            SmbDirentType::FileShare => {
                println!("{}[SHARE] {}", indent, relative_path);
            }
            _ => {
                println!("{}[OTHER] {}", indent, relative_path);
            }
        }
    }

    Ok(())
}

fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error>> {
    // --- Configuration: adjust these values for your environment ---
    let server = std::env::var("SMB_SERVER").unwrap_or_else(|_| "smb://192.168.1.1".to_string());
    let share = std::env::var("SMB_SHARE").unwrap_or_else(|_| "shared".to_string());
    let workgroup = std::env::var("SMB_WORKGROUP").unwrap_or_else(|_| "WORKGROUP".to_string());
    let username = std::env::var("SMB_USERNAME").unwrap_or_else(|_| "guest".to_string());
    let password = std::env::var("SMB_PASSWORD").unwrap_or_else(|_| "".to_string());

    println!("Connecting to {} ...", server);
    println!("Share: {}", share);
    println!("Username: {}", username);
    println!("Workgroup: {}", workgroup);
    println!();

    let client = SmbClient::new(
        SmbCredentials::default()
            .server(&server)
            .share(&share)
            .username(&username)
            .password(&password)
            .workgroup(&workgroup),
        SmbOptions::default()
            .one_share_per_server(true),
    )?;

    let share_path = format!("{}/{}", server, share);

    println!("Listing contents of {} recursively:\n", share_path);

    list_dir_recursive(&client, &share_path, "", 0)?;

    println!("\nDone.");

    Ok(())
}
"
}
```

**Usage:**

Set environment variables before running:

```bash
export SMB_SERVER="smb://192.168.1.100"
export SMB_SHARE="myshare"
export SMB_WORKGROUP="WORKGROUP"
export SMB_USERNAME="myuser"
export SMB_PASSWORD="mypassword"
cargo run
```

**Notes:**
- This uses the `pavao` crate which wraps `libsmbclient` (you need `libsmbclient-dev` / `smbclient` installed on your system: `sudo apt install libsmbclient-dev` on Debian/Ubuntu, or `brew install samba` on macOS).
- The `list_dir` method returns directory entries with type information, letting us distinguish files from directories.
- Errors entering subdirectories (e.g., permission denied) are caught and printed rather than aborting the entire traversal.
- The `.` and `..` entries are skipped to prevent infinite recursion.

