Here's a self-contained example that demonstrates how to properly serialize complex nested data with FlatBuffers in Rust, both single-threaded and multi-threaded. The key insight is that you **cannot** share `FlatBufferBuilder` across threads — instead, you collect/prepare your data in parallel first, then serialize sequentially into the builder.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "flatbuffer-demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
flatbuffers = "24.3.25"
rayon = "1.10"
",
  "main.rs": "use flatbuffers::{FlatBufferBuilder, WIPOffset};
use rayon::prelude::*;

// ============================================================
// Since we don't have a .fbs schema file and flatc-generated code,
// we'll build the FlatBuffer tables manually to demonstrate the
// pattern. This is exactly what the generated code does under
// the hood.
// ============================================================

// ---- Schema-like constants (normally generated by flatc) ----

// FrontMatter table field offsets
const FRONT_MATTER_FIELD_IGNORED_PARSERS: flatbuffers::VOffsetT = 4;
const FRONT_MATTER_FIELD_TITLE: flatbuffers::VOffsetT = 6;

// MdxParsingResult table field offsets
const RESULT_FIELD_CONTENT: flatbuffers::VOffsetT = 4;
const RESULT_FIELD_FRONT_MATTER: flatbuffers::VOffsetT = 6;
const RESULT_FIELD_TAGS: flatbuffers::VOffsetT = 8;

// ---- Helper functions to create tables manually ----

fn create_front_matter<'a>(
    builder: &mut FlatBufferBuilder<'a>,
    title: Option<WIPOffset<&str>>,
    ignored_parsers: Option<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::Vector<'a, flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&'a str>>>>,
) -> WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset> {
    let mut table_builder = builder.start_table();
    if let Some(ip) = ignored_parsers {
        table_builder.push_slot_always(FRONT_MATTER_FIELD_IGNORED_PARSERS, ip);
    }
    if let Some(t) = title {
        table_builder.push_slot_always(FRONT_MATTER_FIELD_TITLE, t);
    }
    let offset = table_builder.finish();
    offset.as_union_value()
}

fn create_mdx_parsing_result<'a>(
    builder: &mut FlatBufferBuilder<'a>,
    content: Option<WIPOffset<&str>>,
    front_matter: Option<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset>>,
    tags: Option<WIPOffset<flatbuffers::Vector<'a, flatbuffers::ForwardsUOffset<&'a str>>>>,
) -> WIPOffset<flatbuffers::UnionWIPOffset> {
    let mut table_builder = builder.start_table();
    if let Some(c) = content {
        table_builder.push_slot_always(RESULT_FIELD_CONTENT, c);
    }
    if let Some(fm) = front_matter {
        table_builder.push_slot_always(RESULT_FIELD_FRONT_MATTER, fm);
    }
    if let Some(t) = tags {
        table_builder.push_slot_always(RESULT_FIELD_TAGS, t);
    }
    let offset = table_builder.finish();
    offset.as_union_value()
}

// ---- Our domain structs ----

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct FrontMatter {
    title: String,
    ignored_parsers: Vec<String>,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct MdxParsingResult {
    content: String,
    front_matter: Option<FrontMatter>,
    tags: Vec<String>,
}

impl MdxParsingResult {
    /// The KEY PATTERN:
    ///
    /// 1. Do all expensive/parallelizable *computation* (string processing,
    ///    data transformation, etc.) using rayon BEFORE touching the builder.
    ///    Collect results into plain Rust types (Vec<String>, etc.).
    ///
    /// 2. Then, in a single-threaded pass, feed everything into the
    ///    FlatBufferBuilder sequentially. The builder is cheap and fast —
    ///    the bottleneck is usually the data preparation, not the
    ///    serialization itself.
    fn serialize_to_flatbuffer(&self) -> Vec<u8> {
        // ==============================================================
        // STEP 1: Parallel data preparation (no builder involved)
        // ==============================================================

        // Example: process ignored_parsers in parallel
        // (imagine these are expensive transformations)
        let prepared_ignored_parsers: Vec<String> = self
            .front_matter
            .as_ref()
            .map(|fm| {
                fm.ignored_parsers
                    .par_iter()
                    .map(|parser| {
                        // Simulate some expensive per-item work
                        format!("processed_{}", parser.to_uppercase())
                    })
                    .collect()
            })
            .unwrap_or_default();

        // Process tags in parallel
        let prepared_tags: Vec<String> = self
            .tags
            .par_iter()
            .map(|tag| {
                // Simulate expensive work
                format!("tag:{}", tag.to_lowercase())
            })
            .collect();

        let prepared_title: Option<String> = self
            .front_matter
            .as_ref()
            .map(|fm| fm.title.to_uppercase());

        // ==============================================================
        // STEP 2: Sequential serialization into FlatBufferBuilder
        //         (this is fast — just memcpy-like operations)
        // ==============================================================
        let mut builder = FlatBufferBuilder::with_capacity(1024);

        // Serialize front matter if present
        let fm_offset = if self.front_matter.is_some() {
            // Create string offsets for ignored parsers
            let ip_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<&str>> = prepared_ignored_parsers
                .iter()
                .map(|s| builder.create_string(s))
                .collect();
            let ip_vector = builder.create_vector(&ip_offsets);

            let title_offset = prepared_title
                .as_ref()
                .map(|t| builder.create_string(t));

            let fm = create_front_matter(&mut builder, title_offset, Some(ip_vector));
            Some(fm)
        } else {
            None
        };

        // Serialize tags
        let tag_offsets: Vec<WIPOffset<&str>> = prepared_tags
            .iter()
            .map(|t| builder.create_string(t))
            .collect();
        let tags_vector = builder.create_vector(&tag_offsets);

        // Serialize content
        let content_offset = builder.create_string(&self.content);

        // Build the root table
        let root = create_mdx_parsing_result(
            &mut builder,
            Some(content_offset),
            fm_offset,
            Some(tags_vector),
        );

        builder.finish_minimal(root);

        builder.finished_data().to_vec()
    }
}

// ---- Demonstrate serializing multiple documents in parallel ----

fn serialize_many_documents(docs: &[MdxParsingResult]) -> Vec<Vec<u8>> {
    // Each document gets its OWN FlatBufferBuilder — no sharing needed!
    // This is embarrassingly parallel.
    docs.par_iter()
        .map(|doc| doc.serialize_to_flatbuffer())
        .collect()
}

fn main() {
    // Create some sample data
    let documents: Vec<MdxParsingResult> = (0..10)
        .map(|i| MdxParsingResult {
            content: format!("# Document {}\n\nThis is the content of document {}.", i, i),
            front_matter: Some(FrontMatter {
                title: format!("Document {} Title", i),
                ignored_parsers: vec![
                    "parser_a".to_string(),
                    "parser_b".to_string(),
                    format!("parser_custom_{}", i),
                ],
            }),
            tags: vec![
                "Rust".to_string(),
                "FlatBuffers".to_string(),
                format!("topic_{}", i),
            ],
        })
        .collect();

    println!("Serializing {} documents in parallel...\n", documents.len());

    // Serialize all documents in parallel (each gets its own builder)
    let serialized = serialize_many_documents(&documents);

    for (i, buf) in serialized.iter().enumerate() {
        println!(
            "Document {}: serialized to {} bytes of FlatBuffer data",
            i,
            buf.len()
        );
    }

    println!("\n--- Single document demo ---\n");

    // Single document serialization
    let single = MdxParsingResult {
        content: "Hello, FlatBuffers from Rust!".to_string(),
        front_matter: Some(FrontMatter {
            title: "My MDX Document".to_string(),
            ignored_parsers: vec!["markdown".to_string(), "html".to_string()],
        }),
        tags: vec!["demo".to_string(), "flatbuffers".to_string()],
    };

    let buf = single.serialize_to_flatbuffer();
    println!("Single document serialized to {} bytes.", buf.len());
    println!("\nKey takeaways:");
    println!("  1. FlatBufferBuilder is NOT Send/Sync — you cannot share it across threads.");
    println!("  2. Do expensive data preparation in parallel FIRST (using rayon/tokio).");
    println!("  3. Then serialize into the builder sequentially — it's just fast memcpy.");
    println!("  4. For multiple documents, give each thread its OWN builder.");
    println!("\nDone!");
}
"
}
```

**Key insights explained:**

1. **`FlatBufferBuilder` is not `Send`/`Sync`** — you simply cannot share it across threads. Don't fight the borrow checker here; it's telling you the right thing.

2. **The pattern is: parallel preparation → sequential serialization.** Do all your expensive computation (string processing, data transformation, network calls, etc.) in parallel using `rayon` or `tokio`, collecting into plain `Vec<String>` or similar types. Then feed everything into the builder in one sequential pass. The builder itself is extremely fast (it's mostly memcpy), so it's not the bottleneck.

3. **For multiple documents, give each its own builder.** This is embarrassingly parallel — `par_iter().map(|doc| doc.serialize_to_flatbuffer())` where each call creates its own `FlatBufferBuilder`.

4. **The closure error you saw** (`cannot borrow builder as mutable in Fn closure`) happens because `par_iter().map()` requires `Fn` (not `FnMut`), and `builder.create_string()` requires `&mut self`. The solution is to not use the builder inside parallel iterators at all.

