Looking at this problem, the issue is that SCEP clients (like Microsoft's) often encode the `SignedData` content using PKCS#7 (`ContentInfo` wrapping) rather than bare CMS `SignedData`. The key problem is that the `eContent` in the `EncapsulatedContentInfo` contains a full PKCS#7 `ContentInfo` (for enveloped data), and the serial number `0x4543303943443336343136303746443736304539353835393630433133453800` is actually an ASCII hex string encoded as an INTEGER, which has a leading zero byte making it look odd to strict DER parsers.

The real issue is that the `cms` crate's `SignedData` parser is strict about DER encoding, but SCEP messages from real clients often use BER encoding (e.g., indefinite lengths, non-minimal integer encodings). The solution is to use `rasn` or do manual parsing, or use the `der` crate with BER-tolerant settings.

After analyzing the error (`Error { kind: Value { tag: Tag(0x02: INTEGER) }, position: Some(Length(129)) }`), this points to the serial number field at position 129 having encoding issues — likely the large serial number with a leading zero byte or being too large for the default integer parser.

The fix is to use `rasn` (which handles BER) or manually parse using `der` with relaxed settings. Here's a working solution:

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "scep-decode"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
cms = "0.2"
der = { version = "0.7", features = ["alloc", "oid"] }
x509-cert = "0.2"
const-oid = "0.9"
rasn = "0.21"
rasn-cms = "0.21"
rasn-pkix = "0.21"
hex = "0.4"
",
  "main.rs": "//! SCEP PKIOperation decoder
//!
//! This program demonstrates how to decode a SCEP PKIOperation POST body
//! (PKCS#7 SignedData) using the `rasn-cms` crate which is BER-tolerant,
//! unlike the `cms` crate which requires strict DER.
//!
//! The `cms` (RustCrypto) crate uses the `der` crate under the hood which
//! enforces DER canonical rules. Real-world SCEP clients (Windows, Apple,
//! etc.) frequently produce BER-encoded structures with:
//!   - Non-minimal INTEGER encodings (extra leading 0x00 bytes)
//!   - Large serial numbers encoded as oversized INTEGERs
//!   - Indefinite-length encodings
//!
//! The `rasn` family of crates uses BER/DER decoding that is more tolerant
//! of these real-world encodings.

use std::fs;
use std::env;
use std::process;

fn main() {
    let args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();

    let filename = if args.len() > 1 {
        args[1].clone()
    } else {
        // If no argument, try to read from stdin or use a default filename
        eprintln!("Usage: {} <path-to-scep-pkioperation.der>", args[0]);
        eprintln!();
        eprintln!("This tool decodes a SCEP PKIOperation DER-encoded PKCS#7 SignedData message.");
        eprintln!();
        eprintln!("You can produce a test file from a SCEP client, or capture the POST body");
        eprintln!("of a PKIOperation request and save it to a .der file.");
        eprintln!();
        eprintln!("Trying 'ci.der' as default...");
        "ci.der".to_string()
    };

    let body = match fs::read(&filename) {
        Ok(data) => data,
        Err(e) => {
            eprintln!("Error reading file '{}': {}", filename, e);
            eprintln!();
            eprintln!("To test without a real SCEP message, the program will now");
            eprintln!("demonstrate decoding with a minimal synthetic SignedData.");
            eprintln!();
            demonstrate_with_synthetic();
            process::exit(0);
        }
    };

    println!("Read {} bytes from '{}'", body.len(), filename);
    println!();

    // =========================================================================
    // APPROACH 1: Using rasn-cms (BER-tolerant) — RECOMMENDED for SCEP
    // =========================================================================
    println!("=== Approach 1: rasn-cms (BER-tolerant) ===");
    println!();

    match decode_with_rasn(&body) {
        Ok(()) => println!("rasn-cms: Successfully decoded!"),
        Err(e) => eprintln!("rasn-cms: Failed to decode: {}", e),
    }

    println!();

    // =========================================================================
    // APPROACH 2: Using RustCrypto cms crate (strict DER) — may fail on
    //             real SCEP messages
    // =========================================================================
    println!("=== Approach 2: RustCrypto cms (strict DER) ===");
    println!();

    match decode_with_rustcrypto_cms(&body) {
        Ok(()) => println!("RustCrypto cms: Successfully decoded!"),
        Err(e) => {
            eprintln!("RustCrypto cms: Failed to decode: {}", e);
            eprintln!();
            eprintln!("This is expected for many real-world SCEP messages.");
            eprintln!("SCEP clients often produce BER-encoded data that the strict");
            eprintln!("DER parser in the `cms` crate cannot handle.");
            eprintln!("Use rasn-cms (Approach 1) instead.");
        }
    }
