Here's a self-contained demonstration that shows how to avoid duplicating `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` downcasting code in Rust by using a trait-based registration approach. Since the original code uses `egui`, I've included it as a dependency and created a minimal working example.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "downcast-demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
eframe = "0.28"
egui = "0.28"
",
  "main.rs": "use eframe::egui;
use egui::{Color32, RichText, Ui};
use std::any::Any;

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The key idea: a trait that lets us register "type‐erased" downcasters for
// Vec<T> and Option<T> without writing each combination by hand.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/// Every concrete T that can appear inside a Vec or Option implements this.
trait Propertyable: Default + 'static {
    fn register_vec(registry: &mut Vec<VecDowncaster>);
    fn register_option(registry: &mut Vec<OptionDowncaster>);
}

// A boxed closure that tries to downcast `&mut dyn Any` to `&mut Vec<T>` and,
// if successful, draws the list UI.  Returns true on success.
type VecDowncaster = Box<dyn Fn(&mut Ui, &str, &mut dyn Any, bool) -> bool>;
type OptionDowncaster = Box<dyn Fn(&mut Ui, &str, &mut dyn Any, bool) -> bool>;

fn make_vec_downcaster<T: Propertyable>() -> VecDowncaster {
    Box::new(|ui, title, value_mut, interactable| {
        if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<Vec<T>>() {
            list_property(ui, title, v, interactable);
            true
        } else {
            false
        }
    })
}

fn make_option_downcaster<T: Propertyable>() -> OptionDowncaster {
    Box::new(|ui, title, value_mut, interactable| {
        if let Some(o) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<Option<T>>() {
            option_property(ui, title, o, interactable);
            true
        } else {
            false
        }
    })
}

impl<T: Default + 'static> Propertyable for T {
    fn register_vec(registry: &mut Vec<VecDowncaster>) {
        registry.push(make_vec_downcaster::<T>());
    }
    fn register_option(registry: &mut Vec<OptionDowncaster>) {
        registry.push(make_option_downcaster::<T>());
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Registry: built once, holds all the Vec/Option downcasters.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

struct DowncastRegistry {
    vec_downcasters: Vec<VecDowncaster>,
    option_downcasters: Vec<OptionDowncaster>,
}

impl DowncastRegistry {
    fn new() -> Self {
        let mut vec_downcasters: Vec<VecDowncaster> = Vec::new();
        let mut option_downcasters: Vec<OptionDowncaster> = Vec::new();

        // ---- Register every inner type ONCE here ----
        macro_rules! register {
            ($($ty:ty),+ $(,)?) => {
                $(
                    <$ty>::register_vec(&mut vec_downcasters);
                    <$ty>::register_option(&mut option_downcasters);
                )+
            };
        }

        register!(
            String,
            i32,
            f32,
            usize,
            bool,
            // Add your own types here, e.g.:
            // DataType,
            // ValueType,
            // NamedTypeValue,
            // ArgumentNamedValue,
        );

        Self {
            vec_downcasters,
            option_downcasters,
        }
    }

    fn try_vec(&self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut dyn Any, interactable: bool) -> bool {
        for dc in &self.vec_downcasters {
            if dc(ui, title, value, interactable) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        false
    }

    fn try_option(&self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut dyn Any, interactable: bool) -> bool {
        for dc in &self.option_downcasters {
            if dc(ui, title, value, interactable) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        false
    }
}

// Use a lazily‐initialised global so we don't rebuild every frame.
fn global_registry() -> &'static DowncastRegistry {
    use std::sync::OnceLock;
    static REG: OnceLock<DowncastRegistry> = OnceLock::new();
    REG.get_or_init(DowncastRegistry::new)
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// The simplified downcast_property – no more per‐type Vec/Option arms!
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub fn downcast_property(
    ui: &mut Ui,
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut (dyn Any + 'static),
    interactable: bool,
) {
    if let Some(s) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<String>() {
        string_property(ui, title, s, interactable);
    } else if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<i32>() {
        i_property(ui, title, v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<f32>() {
        f_property(ui, title, v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<usize>() {
        usize_property(ui, title, v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(v) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<bool>() {
        bool_property(ui, title, v, interactable);
    }
    // ------- automatic Vec<T> and Option<T> handling -------
    else if global_registry().try_vec(ui, title, value_mut, interactable) {
        // handled
    } else if global_registry().try_option(ui, title, value_mut, interactable) {
        // handled
    } else {
        ui.label(
            RichText::new(format!("Field {}: unknown type", title)).color(Color32::LIGHT_RED),
        );
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// list_property / option_property (same logic as the original question)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

pub fn list_property<T: Default + 'static>(
    ui: &mut Ui,
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut Vec<T>,
    interactable: bool,
) {
    egui::CollapsingHeader::new(if title.is_empty() { "list" } else { title })
        .default_open(true)
        .enabled(interactable)
        .show(ui, |ui| {
            if ui.button("➕ Add").clicked() {
                value_mut.push(T::default());
            }
            let mut i = 0;
            while i < value_mut.len() {
                ui.horizontal(|ui| {
                    downcast_property(ui, &format!("[{}]", i), &mut value_mut[i], interactable);
                    if ui.button("❌").on_hover_text("Remove").clicked() {
                        value_mut.remove(i);
                    } else {
                        i += 1;
                    }
                });
                // Because we may have removed an element inside the closure the
                // outer `i` hasn't changed; re‑check length.
                if i >= value_mut.len() {
                    break;
                }
            }
        });
}

pub fn option_property<T: Default + 'static>(
    ui: &mut Ui,
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut Option<T>,
    interactable: bool,
) {
    let mut is_none = value_mut.is_none();
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.checkbox(&mut is_none, "None");
        if is_none {
            *value_mut = None;
        } else if let Some(inner) = value_mut.as_mut() {
            downcast_property(ui, "", inner, interactable);
        } else {
            *value_mut = Some(T::default());
        }
    });
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Leaf property widgets (simplified for the demo)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

fn string_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, v: &mut String, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::TextEdit::singleline(v));
    });
}

fn i_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, v: &mut i32, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::DragValue::new(v));
    });
}

fn f_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, v: &mut f32, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::DragValue::new(v).speed(0.1));
    });
}

fn usize_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, v: &mut usize, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        // DragValue doesn't impl for usize directly, so cast through i64
        let mut tmp = *v as i64;
        if ui
            .add_enabled(interactable, egui::DragValue::new(&mut tmp).clamp_range(0..=i64::MAX))
            .changed()
        {
            *v = tmp.max(0) as usize;
        }
    });
}

fn bool_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, v: &mut bool, interactable: bool) {
    ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::Checkbox::new(v, title));
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Demo application
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

struct DemoApp {
    my_string: String,
    my_int: i32,
    my_float: f32,
    my_bool: bool,
    my_vec_strings: Vec<String>,
    my_vec_ints: Vec<i32>,
    my_vec_floats: Vec<f32>,
    my_opt_string: Option<String>,
    my_opt_i32: Option<i32>,
    my_opt_bool: Option<bool>,
}

impl Default for DemoApp {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            my_string: "hello".into(),
            my_int: 42,
            my_float: 3.14,
            my_bool: true,
            my_vec_strings: vec!["a".into(), "b".into()],
            my_vec_ints: vec![1, 2, 3],
            my_vec_floats: vec![0.5, 1.5],
            my_opt_string: Some("optional".into()),
            my_opt_i32: None,
            my_opt_bool: Some(false),
        }
    }
}

impl eframe::App for DemoApp {
    fn update(&mut self, ctx: &egui::Context, _frame: &mut eframe::Frame) {
        egui::CentralPanel::default().show(ctx, |ui| {
            ui.heading("Downcast demo – Vec<T> & Option<T> handled automatically");
            ui.separator();

            // We build a list of (name, &mut dyn Any) pairs – exactly the kind
            // of thing a reflection / properties system would produce.
            let fields: Vec<(&str, &mut dyn Any)> = vec![
                ("my_string", &mut self.my_string),
                ("my_int", &mut self.my_int),
                ("my_float", &mut self.my_float),
                ("my_bool", &mut self.my_bool),
                ("my_vec_strings", &mut self.my_vec_strings),
                ("my_vec_ints", &mut self.my_vec_ints),
                ("my_vec_floats", &mut self.my_vec_floats),
                ("my_opt_string", &mut self.my_opt_string),
                ("my_opt_i32", &mut self.my_opt_i32),
                ("my_opt_bool", &mut self.my_opt_bool),
            ];

            for (name, value) in fields {
                downcast_property(ui, name, value, true);
                ui.add_space(4.0);
            }
        });
    }
}

fn main() -> eframe::Result<()> {
    let options = eframe::NativeOptions {
        viewport: egui::ViewportBuilder::default().with_inner_size([600.0, 700.0]),
        ..Default::default()
    };
    eframe::run_native(
        "Downcast Vec/Option Demo",
        options,
        Box::new(|_cc| Ok(Box::new(DemoApp::default()))),
    )
}
"
}
```

**How it works (the key insight):**

1. **`DowncastRegistry`** holds two `Vec`s of boxed closures — one for `Vec<T>` downcasters, one for `Option<T>` downcasters.

2. **`make_vec_downcaster::<T>()`** and **`make_option_downcaster::<T>()`** each produce a closure that tries `downcast_mut::<Vec<T>>()` or `downcast_mut::<Option<T>>()` and calls the appropriate UI function on success.

3. You **register types once** via the `register!` macro inside `DowncastRegistry::new()`:
   ```rust
   register!(String, i32, f32, usize, bool, DataType, ...);
   ```
   Adding a new type means adding **one** entry here — not two extra `else if` arms (one for `Vec<T>`, one for `Option<T>`).

4. In `downcast_property`, instead of N branches for `Vec<T>` and M branches for `Option<T>`, you just call:
   ```rust
   global_registry().try_vec(ui, title, value_mut, interactable)
   global_registry().try_option(ui, title, value_mut, interactable)
   ```

This eliminates the combinatorial explosion while still using Rust's `Any` downcasting (which requires concrete types at compile time — the registry just generates them in one place).

