{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "span-rehydrate-demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
opentelemetry = { version = "0.27", features = ["trace"] }
opentelemetry_sdk = { version = "0.27", features = ["rt-tokio"] }
opentelemetry-stdout = { version = "0.27", features = ["trace"] }
tracing = "0.1"
tracing-opentelemetry = "0.28"
tracing-subscriber = { version = "0.3", features = ["env-filter", "registry"] }
tokio = { version = "1", features = ["full"] }
",
  "main.rs": "//! Demonstrates how to "rehydrate" (re-attach) a parent span across async
//! task / callback boundaries using `tracing` + OpenTelemetry.
//!
//! The key idea:
//!   1. Create a long-lived *request* span.
//!   2. Capture a `tracing::Span` handle and store it in your shared context.
//!   3. In every subsequent stage callback, enter that span (or use
//!      `instrument()` with it as a parent) so the child spans are nested
//!      under the original request span – even if they run on a different
//!      thread / task.

use opentelemetry::trace::TracerProvider;
use opentelemetry_sdk::{
    trace::SdkTracerProvider,
    Resource,
};
use opentelemetry::KeyValue;
use tracing_opentelemetry::OpenTelemetryLayer;
use tracing_subscriber::{layer::SubscriberExt, util::SubscriberInitExt, Registry};

use std::sync::Arc;
use tracing::{info, info_span, Instrument, Span};

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Simulated "shared context" that Pingora (or any framework) passes between
// stage callbacks.  The crucial field is `request_span`.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
struct MyCtx {
    /// The parent / request-level span handle that we carry across callbacks.
    request_span: Span,
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Simulated stage callbacks – each may be called on an arbitrary Tokio task.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/// Stage 1: e.g. request_filter
async fn stage_1(ctx: &MyCtx) {
    // Create a child span whose parent is the stored request span.
    // `follows_from` is *not* what we want here; we need a true parent.
    // Using `.instrument()` with a span that was created while the parent
    // was entered achieves that.
    async {
        let span = info_span!(parent: &ctx.request_span, "stage_1");
        async {
            info!("doing stage-1 work");
            tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(50)).await;
            info!("stage-1 complete");
        }
        .instrument(span)
        .await;
    }
    .await;
}

/// Stage 2: e.g. upstream_peer
async fn stage_2(ctx: &MyCtx) {
    let span = info_span!(parent: &ctx.request_span, "stage_2");
    async {
        info!("doing stage-2 work");
        tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(40)).await;
        info!("stage-2 complete");
    }
    .instrument(span)
    .await;
}

/// Stage 3: e.g. upstream request
async fn stage_upstream(ctx: &MyCtx) {
    let span = info_span!(parent: &ctx.request_span, "upstream");
    async {
        info!("calling upstream");
        tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_millis(60)).await;
        info!("upstream responded");
    }
    .instrument(span)
    .await;
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Entrypoint
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    // ---- set up OpenTelemetry + tracing-subscriber ----

    let exporter = opentelemetry_stdout::SpanExporter::default();

    let provider = SdkTracerProvider::builder()
        .with_simple_exporter(exporter)
        .with_resource(Resource::new(vec![KeyValue::new(
            "service.name",
            "span-rehydrate-demo",
        )]))
        .build();

    let tracer = provider.tracer("demo");

    // Build the subscriber: Registry + OpenTelemetry layer
    Registry::default()
        .with(OpenTelemetryLayer::new(tracer))
        .with(
            tracing_subscriber::fmt::layer()
                .with_target(false)
                .compact(),
        )
        .init();

    // ---- simulate a request lifecycle ----

    // 1. Create the top-level request span and keep a handle.
    let request_span = info_span!("request", req.id = "abc-123");

    // 2. Store the span handle in the shared context.
    let ctx = Arc::new(MyCtx {
        request_span: request_span.clone(),
    });

    // 3. Simulate Pingora (or Tokio) calling stage callbacks on separate
    //    tasks / threads.  Each one "rehydrates" the parent span via the
    //    context.

    // We enter the request span briefly just to make sure it is "active"
    // at creation time, but the callbacks do NOT rely on it being the
    // current span – they explicitly use `parent: &ctx.request_span`.
    let _enter = request_span.enter();
    info!("request started");
    drop(_enter);

    // -- spawn on separate tasks to prove cross-task propagation --
    let c = ctx.clone();
    let h1 = tokio::spawn(async move {
        stage_1(&c).await;
    });
    h1.await.unwrap();

    let c = ctx.clone();
    let h2 = tokio::spawn(async move {
        stage_2(&c).await;
    });
    h2.await.unwrap();

    let c = ctx.clone();
    let h3 = tokio::spawn(async move {
        stage_upstream(&c).await;
    });
    h3.await.unwrap();

    // Close the request span
    request_span.in_scope(|| {
        info!("request finished");
    });
    drop(request_span);

    // Flush traces
    provider.shutdown().expect("failed to shut down provider");

    println!("\n=== Done. Spans printed above in OpenTelemetry JSON format ===");
    println!("Look for the parent/child relationship: request -> stage_1, stage_2, upstream");
}
"
}
```

### How it works

The core technique is straightforward:

1. **Create a request-level `tracing::Span`** and **store the `Span` handle** in your shared context struct (`MyCtx`). A `tracing::Span` is `Send + Sync` and cheap to clone.

2. **In each stage callback**, create a new child span using the **`parent:` directive**:
   ```rust
   let span = info_span!(parent: &ctx.request_span, "stage_1");
   ```
   This explicitly sets the parent regardless of what the "current" span is on the executing thread/task.

3. **`.instrument(span)`** the async block with that child span so all work inside is attributed correctly.

This avoids any reliance on thread-local or task-local span context — you're explicitly wiring the parent via the stored handle, which works perfectly across Tokio task boundaries and is exactly what Pingora's callback model requires.

