Here's a solution that demonstrates how to work around the `enum_dispatch` same-crate limitation by using a procedural-macro-free approach with a custom macro that generates the enum dispatch boilerplate. This keeps the three-layer architecture intact (abstract layer, implementation layer, business layer) all demonstrated in a single file.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "enum_dispatch_design"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
",
  "main.rs": "// =============================================================================
// This file demonstrates how to solve the enum_dispatch cross-crate limitation
// by using a declarative macro to generate the dispatching enum + impl.
//
// Architecture:
//   - `al` module  = Abstract Layer (traits, generic data structures)
//   - `il` module  = Implementation Layer (concrete structs implementing traits)
//   - `bl` module  = Business Layer (configuration, orchestration)
//
// The key insight: instead of relying on the `enum_dispatch` crate (which
// requires the trait and enum in the same crate), we define a declarative
// macro in the abstract layer that *generates* the enum and its trait impl
// at the call site (the business layer). This avoids any circular dependency.
// =============================================================================

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Abstract Layer (would be its own crate: `al`)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
mod al {
    /// The trait with many methods (here we show a representative subset).
    /// In production this could have 20+ methods.
    pub trait Rest {
        fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String;
        fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String;
        fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String;
        fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String;
        fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String;
        fn head(&self, url: &str) -> String;
        fn options(&self, url: &str) -> String;
        fn name(&self) -> &'static str;
    }

    /// Declarative macro that generates an enum and implements `Rest` via
    /// static dispatch (match on each variant). This macro lives in `al` so
    /// any downstream crate can invoke it without causing a dependency cycle.
    ///
    /// Usage:
    /// ```
    /// al::define_rest_enum! {
    ///     pub enum Item {
    ///         Foo(il::Foo),
    ///         Boo(il::Boo),
    ///     }
    /// }
    /// ```
    #[macro_export]
    macro_rules! define_rest_enum {
        (
            $(#[$meta:meta])*
            $vis:vis enum $Enum:ident {
                $( $Variant:ident ( $Ty:ty ) ),* $(,)?
            }
        ) => {
            // Generate the enum with From impls
            $(#[$meta])*
            $vis enum $Enum {
                $( $Variant($Ty), )*
            }

            // Generate From<T> for each variant
            $(
                impl From<$Ty> for $Enum {
                    fn from(v: $Ty) -> Self {
                        $Enum::$Variant(v)
                    }
                }
            )*

            // Implement Rest by dispatching every method to the inner type
            impl $crate::al::Rest for $Enum {
                fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.get(url), )* }
                }
                fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.post(url, body), )* }
                }
                fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.put(url, body), )* }
                }
                fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.delete(url), )* }
                }
                fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.patch(url, body), )* }
                }
                fn head(&self, url: &str) -> String {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.head(url), )* }
                }
                fn options(&self, url: &str) -> String {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.options(url), )* }
                }
                fn name(&self) -> &'static str {
                    match self { $( $Enum::$Variant(inner) => inner.name(), )* }
                }
            }
        };
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Implementation Layer (would be its own crate: `il`, depends on `al`)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
mod il {
    use crate::al::Rest;

    /// First implementation of `Rest`.
    pub struct Foo {
        pub base_url: String,
    }

    impl Rest for Foo {
        fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo GET {}/{}", self.base_url, url)
        }
        fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo POST {}/{} body={}", self.base_url, url, body)
        }
        fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo PUT {}/{} body={}", self.base_url, url, body)
        }
        fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo DELETE {}/{}", self.base_url, url)
        }
        fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo PATCH {}/{} body={}", self.base_url, url, body)
        }
        fn head(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo HEAD {}/{}", self.base_url, url)
        }
        fn options(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Foo OPTIONS {}/{}", self.base_url, url)
        }
        fn name(&self) -> &'static str {
            "Foo"
        }
    }

    /// Second implementation of `Rest`.
    pub struct Boo {
        pub token: String,
    }

    impl Rest for Boo {
        fn get(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo GET {} (token={})", url, self.token)
        }
        fn post(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo POST {} body={} (token={})", url, body, self.token)
        }
        fn put(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo PUT {} body={} (token={})", url, body, self.token)
        }
        fn delete(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo DELETE {} (token={})", url, self.token)
        }
        fn patch(&self, url: &str, body: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo PATCH {} body={} (token={})", url, body, self.token)
        }
        fn head(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo HEAD {} (token={})", url, self.token)
        }
        fn options(&self, url: &str) -> String {
            format!("Boo OPTIONS {} (token={})", url, self.token)
        }
        fn name(&self) -> &'static str {
            "Boo"
        }
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Business Layer (would be its own crate: `bl`, depends on `al` and `il`)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
mod bl {
    use crate::al::Rest;
    use crate::il::{Foo, Boo};

    // Use the macro from `al` to generate the dispatching enum.
    // This is the equivalent of:
    //   #[enum_dispatch(Rest)]
    //   pub enum Item { Foo, Boo }
    // but works across crate boundaries.
    crate::define_rest_enum! {
        pub enum Item {
            Foo(Foo),
            Boo(Boo),
        }
    }

    /// A function that works with any `Item` using static dispatch.
    /// No `dyn`, no vtable — the compiler monomorphizes the match arms.
    pub fn process(item: &Item) {
        println!("--- Processing via [{}] ---", item.name());
        println!("  {}", item.get("users/1"));
        println!("  {}", item.post("users", r#"{"name":"Alice"}"#));
        println!("  {}", item.put("users/1", r#"{"name":"Bob"}"#));
        println!("  {}", item.delete("users/1"));
        println!("  {}", item.patch("users/1", r#"{"age":30}"#));
        println!("  {}", item.head("users"));
        println!("  {}", item.options("users"));
        println!();
    }

    /// Demonstrate choosing an implementation at runtime (e.g., from config)
    /// while still benefiting from static dispatch inside the enum.
    pub fn run(use_foo: bool) {
        let item: Item = if use_foo {
            Foo { base_url: "https://api.foo.com".into() }.into()
        } else {
            Boo { token: "secret-token-42".into() }.into()
        };
        process(&item);
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Entry point
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn main() {
    println!("=== Enum Dispatch Design Without Crate Cycle ===");
    println!();

    // Use the Foo backend
    bl::run(true);

    // Use the Boo backend
    bl::run(false);

    // We can also collect heterogeneous items in a Vec<Item> — still static dispatch
    use crate::al::Rest;
    let items: Vec<bl::Item> = vec![
        il::Foo { base_url: "https://example.com".into() }.into(),
        il::Boo { token: "tok-abc".into() }.into(),
    ];

    println!("=== Iterating over a Vec<Item> ===");
    for item in &items {
        println!("  {} -> {}", item.name(), item.get("ping"));
    }
}
"
}
```

### How This Solves the Problem

1. **No circular dependencies**: The macro `define_rest_enum!` is defined in `al` (abstract layer). It gets *invoked* in `bl` (business layer). The dependency graph remains:
   - `il` → `al`
   - `bl` → `al` + `il`

2. **Static dispatch**: The generated `match` arms give the compiler full type information for each variant — no vtable, no `dyn Trait`, just like `enum_dispatch`.

3. **Scales to 20+ methods**: You only write each method signature once in the trait and once in the macro's `impl` block. Each variant's delegation is a single match arm per method, auto-generated by the macro.

4. **Easy to extend**: Adding a new `impl` (e.g., `Qux`) only requires adding `Qux(il::Qux)` to the macro invocation in `bl`.

5. **Cross-crate compatible**: When split into real crates, `define_rest_enum!` is exported via `#[macro_export]` and can be called from any downstream crate.

