Here's a self-contained demonstration that shows how to avoid duplicating `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` downcasting code in Rust by using a trait-object approach with a custom registry. The key insight is that `dyn Any` erases the type, so you **cannot** generically downcast to "any `Vec<T>`" or "any `Option<T>`" at runtime — Rust's type system doesn't support that. Instead, you register type-erased "handlers" for each concrete type once, and then use macros to eliminate the boilerplate.

```json
{
  "Cargo.toml": "[package]
name = "downcast_demo"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
",
  "main.rs": "use std::any::Any;
use std::any::TypeId;
use std::collections::HashMap;

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Simulated UI (stand-in for egui)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
struct Ui {
    indent: usize,
}

impl Ui {
    fn new() -> Self { Self { indent: 0 } }
    fn label(&self, text: &str) {
        println!("{:indent$}{}", "", text, indent = self.indent * 2);
    }
    fn indented(&mut self) -> &mut Self {
        self.indent += 1;
        self
    }
    fn dedented(&mut self) -> &mut Self {
        self.indent = self.indent.saturating_sub(1);
        self
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Leaf property renderers
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn string_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value: &mut String, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("[String] {}: \"{}\"", title, value));
}

fn i32_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value: &mut i32, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("[i32]    {}: {}", title, value));
}

fn f32_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value: &mut f32, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("[f32]    {}: {}", title, value));
}

fn bool_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value: &mut bool, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("[bool]   {}: {}", title, value));
}

fn usize_property(ui: &Ui, title: &str, value: &mut usize, _interactable: bool) {
    ui.label(&format!("[usize]  {}: {}", title, value));
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Generic list_property and option_property that call back into the registry
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn list_property<T: Default + 'static>(
    ui: &mut Ui,
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut Vec<T>,
    interactable: bool,
    registry: &PropertyRegistry,
) {
    ui.label(&format!("[Vec<{}>] {} (len={}):", std::any::type_name::<T>(), title, value_mut.len()));
    ui.indented();
    for (i, item) in value_mut.iter_mut().enumerate() {
        registry.downcast_property(ui, &format!("[{}]", i), item, interactable);
    }
    ui.dedented();
}

fn option_property<T: Default + 'static>(
    ui: &mut Ui,
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut Option<T>,
    interactable: bool,
    registry: &PropertyRegistry,
) {
    match value_mut {
        Some(inner) => {
            ui.label(&format!("[Option<{}>] {} = Some:", std::any::type_name::<T>(), title));
            ui.indented();
            registry.downcast_property(ui, "", inner, interactable);
            ui.dedented();
        }
        None => {
            ui.label(&format!("[Option<{}>] {} = None", std::any::type_name::<T>(), title));
        }
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// PropertyRegistry: a table of type-erased handlers
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
type Handler = Box<dyn Fn(&mut Ui, &str, &mut dyn Any, bool, &PropertyRegistry) -> bool>;

struct PropertyRegistry {
    handlers: Vec<(TypeId, Handler)>,
}

impl PropertyRegistry {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            handlers: Vec::new(),
        }
    }

    /// Register a handler for a specific concrete type.
    fn register<T: 'static>(
        &mut self,
        handler: impl Fn(&mut Ui, &str, &mut T, bool, &PropertyRegistry) + 'static,
    ) {
        let tid = TypeId::of::<T>();
        self.handlers.push((
            tid,
            Box::new(move |ui, title, any_val, interactable, reg| {
                if let Some(v) = any_val.downcast_mut::<T>() {
                    handler(ui, title, v, interactable, reg);
                    true
                } else {
                    false
                }
            }),
        ));
    }

    fn downcast_property(
        &self,
        ui: &mut Ui,
        title: &str,
        value_mut: &mut dyn Any,
        interactable: bool,
    ) {
        let tid = (*value_mut).type_id();
        for (registered_tid, handler) in &self.handlers {
            if *registered_tid == tid {
                if handler(ui, title, value_mut, interactable, self) {
                    return;
                }
            }
        }
        ui.label(&format!(
            "[UNKNOWN] Field '{}': unknown type (TypeId={:?})",
            title, tid
        ));
    }
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Macros to bulk-register Vec<T> and Option<T> for many inner types at once
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

/// Register a leaf/scalar type.
macro_rules! register_leaf {
    ($registry:expr, $T:ty, $func:ident) => {
        $registry.register::<$T>(|ui, title, v, interactable, _reg| {
            $func(ui, title, v, interactable);
        });
    };
}

/// For each type in the list, register `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` handlers.
macro_rules! register_vec_and_option {
    ($registry:expr, $($T:ty),+ $(,)?) => {
        $(
            $registry.register::<Vec<$T>>(|ui, title, v, interactable, reg| {
                list_property(ui, title, v, interactable, reg);
            });
            $registry.register::<Option<$T>>(|ui, title, v, interactable, reg| {
                option_property(ui, title, v, interactable, reg);
            });
        )+
    };
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Build the registry once
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn build_registry() -> PropertyRegistry {
    let mut reg = PropertyRegistry::new();

    // 1) Register leaf types
    register_leaf!(reg, String, string_property);
    register_leaf!(reg, i32, i32_property);
    register_leaf!(reg, f32, f32_property);
    register_leaf!(reg, bool, bool_property);
    register_leaf!(reg, usize, usize_property);

    // 2) Register Vec<T> and Option<T> for ALL types you care about — ONE line each!
    //    Add new types here and they automatically get Vec + Option support.
    register_vec_and_option!(reg, String, i32, f32, bool, usize);

    // You can also register standalone Option/Vec for types that don't need both:
    // reg.register::<Option<MyCustomType>>(...);

    reg
}

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Demo structs to exercise the system
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
fn main() {
    let registry = build_registry();
    let mut ui = Ui::new();
    let interactable = true;

    println!("=== Scalar properties ===");
    {
        let mut s = String::from("hello");
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "my_string", &mut s, interactable);

        let mut i: i32 = 42;
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "my_int", &mut i, interactable);

        let mut f: f32 = 3.14;
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "my_float", &mut f, interactable);

        let mut b: bool = true;
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "my_bool", &mut b, interactable);
    }

    println!();
    println!("=== Vec properties ===");
    {
        let mut v: Vec<String> = vec!["alpha".into(), "beta".into()];
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "string_list", &mut v, interactable);

        let mut v2: Vec<i32> = vec![10, 20, 30];
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "int_list", &mut v2, interactable);

        let mut v3: Vec<f32> = vec![1.1, 2.2];
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "float_list", &mut v3, interactable);

        let mut v4: Vec<bool> = vec![true, false, true];
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "bool_list", &mut v4, interactable);
    }

    println!();
    println!("=== Option properties ===");
    {
        let mut o1: Option<String> = Some("world".into());
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "opt_string", &mut o1, interactable);

        let mut o2: Option<i32> = None;
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "opt_int", &mut o2, interactable);

        let mut o3: Option<usize> = Some(99);
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "opt_usize", &mut o3, interactable);
    }

    println!();
    println!("=== Unknown type ===");
    {
        let mut unknown: u64 = 12345;
        registry.downcast_property(&mut ui, "mystery", &mut unknown, interactable);
    }

    println!();
    println!("=== Nested: Vec<Vec<i32>> (if registered) ===");
    {
        // This would print "unknown" unless we also register Vec<Vec<i32>>.
        // Let's show how easy it is to add:
        // For demo, we rebuild with the extra registration:
        let mut reg2 = build_registry();
        register_vec_and_option!(reg2, Vec<i32>);

        let mut nested: Vec<Vec<i32>> = vec![vec![1, 2], vec![3, 4, 5]];
        reg2.downcast_property(&mut ui, "nested_list", &mut nested, interactable);
    }
}
"
}
```

**Key takeaways shown in this demo:**

1. **You cannot generically downcast `dyn Any` to "any `Vec<T>`"** in Rust — `Vec<String>` and `Vec<i32>` are entirely different types at runtime. There's no built-in way to ask "is this some kind of `Vec`?"

2. **The solution is a registry + macros.** The `register_vec_and_option!` macro takes a list of types and generates both `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` handler registrations for each one in a single line. Adding a new type requires adding just one identifier to the macro invocation.

3. **The `PropertyRegistry`** stores type-erased handler closures keyed by `TypeId`, so `downcast_property` simply looks up the handler and calls it — no giant `if/else` chain needed.

4. **Recursive nesting works**: if you register `Vec<Vec<i32>>`, the inner `Vec<i32>` handler is found automatically since `list_property` calls back into the registry.

